<HEADLINE> Manila Refuses to Replace Chief Hostage Crisis Negotiator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government rejected
on Sunday the Abu Sayyaf's latest demand to replace its chief
negotiator in talks for the release of the hostages taken by the
group.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Press Secretary Ricardo Puno said at the
Presidential Office that the government will not heed the Moslem
extremist group's demand over the weekend to replace chief
negotiator Robert Aventajado.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf slammed Aventajado for hinting at the
possibility of using military means to solve the hostage crisis if
negotiations fail.
</P>
<P>
Aventajado has been in the negotiating team since mid-May. He
had replaced Nur Misuari, governor of the Autonomous Region for
Muslim Mindanao, upon an earlier demand by the Abu Sayyaf.
</P>
<P>
Puno said, "The government will never allow the Abu Sayyaf to
dictate us as to who will be our negotiators."
</P>
<P>
He called the demand just another tactic of the Abu Sayyaf to
prolong the hostage crisis which is now on its 50th day.
</P>
<P>
The press secretary also dismissed speculations that the
government's refusal to grant the Abu Sayyaf's latest demand would
put at risk the safety of the group's 21 mostly foreign hostages
in Jolo island in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf, which kidnapped the hostages from the Sipadan
Island resort in Malaysia on April 23, was said to have separated
its captives into two groups for fear of government military
rescue operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
