<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Day Sailing Record Broken </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The giant catamaran Club Med has
shattered the world record for the distance sailed in 24 hours,
covering 625.7 nautical miles to improve the old record by more
than 45 miles.
</P>
<P>
Jointly skippered by New Zealander Grant Dalton and Frenchman
Bruno Peyron, the 33.50-meter sailing machine with a crew of 14 on
board averaged 26.07 knots during the 24 hour period.
</P>
<P>
The previous record, of 580 miles, was achieved by American
adventurer, sailor and balloonist Steve Fossett, in the Pacific
Ocean off New Zealand in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Club Med catamaran was launched on May 8 and is attempting
to break the trans-Atlantic record from Cadiz to San Salvador in
the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
At the time they set the new record, the vessel was west of the
Canary Islands in the north Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
Grant Dalton is a veteran of six Whitbread Round the World
Races, while Peyron is a previous holder of the 24 hour record,
once achieving 547 nautical miles in his catamaran Explorer.
</P>
</TEXT>
