<HEADLINE> Irish Premier on Irish-Asian Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMERICK, Ireland, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Irish Prime Minister
Bertin Ahern said here on Monday that Ireland was delighted at the
progress which has been made in China's accession to the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
"When China joins, we will have an inclusive international
trade system - without Chinese membership the prospects for a
meaningful reform of international trading rule has been
impossible," Ahern said at the opening of the fourth Asia-Europe
Young Leaders Symposium.
</P>
<P>
"As a small trading island, we recognize the need for
meaningful negotiations in the millennium round and have a large
stake in further moves to promote more free and fair trade," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
He said Ireland, and its partners in the European Union, have
much to learn from Asia -- the world's largest and most populous
continent and over the past three decades the engine of growth for
the world economy.
</P>
<P>
The Irish prime minister added Ireland will encourage Irish
investors and traders to reach out to Asia. "In a shrinking global
economy, Asia and Europe will of course be competitors, but we can
also be partners and, can offer our peoples new opportunities that
benefit everyone," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Irish government has adopted an Asian
Strategy,designed to put in place a comprehensive pro-active
political and economic policy context for the establishment of
stronger, deeper and more durable links with the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
