<HEADLINE> Mexico, U.S. to Build New Gas Pipeline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Companies involved in this project are Sempra and Pacific Gas
and Electric, of United States, and Grupo Proxima of Mexico,
according to reports coming from American city of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
Tubing will have a length of 341 kilometers, a cost of 230
million U.S. dollars and a capability for transferring 400 million
cubic feet a day.
</P>
<P>
Tubing will take gas from a firm at El Paso (Texas) to Rosarito
locality, in Baja California state (Mexico).
</P>
<P>
Both firms ended two weeks ago the building of a pipeline that
provides gas from southern California (United States) to a
thermoelectric plant at Rosarito locality, Baja California (Mexico)
.
</P>
<P>
In case the new pipeline is approved, it'll go into operation
in year 2003, said these firms in a communique. The go-ahead for
this pipeline's building depends on United States' Regulating
Commission and its Mexican similar. 
</P>
