<HEADLINE> U.N. Ready to Play Part in OAU Plan for Horn of Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations said
Monday that it was ready to play a part in a plan by the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) to end the war between Eritrea
and Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations welcomes Eritrea's agreement last Friday
to the OAU's peace plan, as well as Ethiopia's announced agreement
in principle to the plan," U.N. Spokesman Fred Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
"A three-person planning mission from the (United Nations)
Department of Peacekeeping Operations is on standby to travel to
Algiers to discuss a possible U.N. role under an agreed agreement
upon peace plan between the two parties," he said.
</P>
<P>
The two warring countries agreed to the plan after almost two
weeks of indirect talks in Algiers, capital of Algeria, which
currently holds the chairmanship of the OAU.
</P>
<P>
The plan involves an immediate cease-fire between the two Horn
of Africa countries, which resumed a two-year border war on May 12,
followed by deployment of a U.N. peacekeeping force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
