<HEADLINE> Group of Rio Summit Preparation Tasks Begin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Preparation tasks for this summit began this Monday with
meetings of coordinators, technicians and assessors of countries
members of Group of Rio at Conventions Center, in Cartegena.
</P>
<P>
On June 13, vice foreign ministers will review and adjust
working agenda of foreign  ministers, who'll meet on June 14.
</P>
<P>
The agenda will include the analysis of main political,
economic, trade and social issues Latin America's countries are
facing.
</P>
<P>
Questions of highest interest will concentrate on looking for
a Latin American stance for Millennium Summit, convoked by United
Nations Organization in New York for coming September, and
challenges in face of globalization.
</P>
<P>
This group will analyze UN's role in the 21st century, document
presented to General Secretary of this organization, Kofi Annan,
and will look to institutionalize regional talks with European
Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Leaders will discuss the strengthening of democracy,
international
financial crisis and its effects upon Latin America's economies,
and also the recent entry to this forum of Central American
countries and Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of this group will ponder Peru's controversial election
process, where President Alberto Fujimori was reelected, and will
examine Paraguay's situation.
</P>
<P>
Present at the summit will be Presidents of Argentina, Bolivia,
Brazil, Colombia, Chile, Ecuador, Guyana, Mexico, Panama, Peru,
Uruguay and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
Also participating at this meeting for first time will be
heads of State of Central America's nations (Costa Rica, Guatemala,
El Salvador, Honduras and Nicaragua) and of Dominican Republic,
which after this summit are full members.
</P>
<P>
President of Paraguay, Luis Gonzalez Macchi, cancelled his
attendance to Group of Rio Summit, owing to his country's
disturbed social situation, and will be represented by Foreign
Relations Minister, Juan Esteban Aguirre.
</P>
<P>
Group of Rio was founded on December 16, 1986, and called Group
of the Eight initially, including Mexico, Colombia, Venezuela and
Panama and Argentina, Peru, Brazil and Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
With successive expansions, this mechanism adopted the name of
Group of Rio at Foreign Ministers Meeting in March 1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
