<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina Satisfied with Oviedo's Capture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, June 12 (Xinhua)-- Agentine Interior Minister
Federico Storani said Monday he is happy that Paraguayan ex-
General Lino Oviedo has been captured.
</P>
<P>
In statements to the press, this high Argentine official said
that Oviedo's detention will allow them to thoroughly investigate
the level of participation in killings attributed to him,
including the assassination of the country's Vice President Luis
Maria Argana.
</P>
<P>
Storani said that Oviedo's capture in Brazilian city of Foz de
Iguazu confirms what Argentina's government declared, that Oviedo
has no place to hide on this country's territory.
</P>
<P>
This is Argentine government's first reaction after the
Paraguayan ex-General was captured Sunday, and taken on Monday to
Brasilia.
</P>
<P>
Paraguay's failed coup leader Lino Oviedo arrived in Brasilia
under police custody.
</P>
<P>
Oviedo was arrested in the southern Brazilian town of Foz do
Iguazu, overlooking one of the world's biggest waterfalls, Sunday
afternoon after regional authorities launched a manhunt in two
countries that lasted six months.
</P>
<P>
Paraguay's government intensified its hunt for Oviedo after
light tanks blew a hole in Congress in another failed military
uprising in Asuncion last month.
</P>
<P>
Oviedo evaded Paraguayan authorities ever since he fled
Asuncion in March 1999 following the murder of Vice President Luis
Maria Argana, which Oviedo allegedly co-plotted with his former
running mate and President Raul Cubas. Cubas was ousted in the
ensuing violence and Brazil granted him exile in an attempt to
defuse a potentially explosive situation.
</P>
<P>
Oviedo went to Argentina at the same time but quickly violated
his asylum terms in Buenos Aires by speaking to the press on
political issues. He was confined to Argentina's icy south where
he complained that strong winds would ruin his hair transplant.
</P>
<P>
He escaped in December last year and was unseen until Sunday.
But he gave regular interviews saying he was saying he was
somewhere in Paraguay, planning his return to power. He has denied
involvement in last month's uprising.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
