<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interactive TV Audience to Experience Dramatic Growth Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 12 (Xinhua) -- After years of disappointing
results, the interactive television market is finally taking off,
according to a new study released Monday.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this year, said U.S. communications research firm
Strategy Analytics, nearly 17 million homes worldwide will have
access to online shopping, banking, e-mail and other services via
their TV sets.
</P>
<P>
According to the firm's study, Europe is leading the way in
rolling out interactive TV services, and accounts for 81 percent
of the world market. But operators in the Untied States and
elsewhere are expected to introduce interactive service over the
next year or so. By 2005, Strategy Analytics projects that 179
million homes worldwide will access online services via their TV
sets.
</P>
<P>
Interactive services are being established on the back of
worldwide adoption of digital television. Operators' strategies
involve building the initial customer base with premium television
services and then offering those customers enhanced interactive
services at no extra cost. The most advanced operators now offer a
range of services such as Internet e-mail, online shopping,
financial services and interactive programming.
</P>
<P>
"Interactive television gives broadcasters the chance to
compete with Internet service providers for e-commerce revenues,"
Strategy Analytics said. "Next-generation advanced set-top boxes
will also position TV service providers as key gateway owners in
tomorrow's interactive home."
</P>
<P>
The study also identifies the world leading digital TV markets.
The UK is now the world's most advanced market, with an expected
29 percent of homes having switched to digital by the end of 2000,
followed by the U.S. (24 percent), France (15 percent) and Spain (
15 percent). 
</P>
</TEXT>
