<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Fall On Corporate Profit Warnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks ended lower
Monday as a couple of companies warned that they would miss profit
predication in the current and forthcoming quarters under the
pressure of higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 49.85 at 10,564.21
and the technology heavy Nasdaq composite index fell 106.93 at 3,
767.91.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index fell 10.95 at 1,446.00.
</P>
<P>
The market fell after Citrix said expansion of its core
business in large enterprise is slower than expected and its
earnings will miss estimates in the coming quarter. The company
plunged 47 percent to 22 U.S. dollars per share.
</P>
<P>
The warning dragged the Nasdaq index down and led the broad
market lower.
</P>
<P>
Another warning from Home Depot also helped to drive stocks
lower. The retailer said its earnings will miss expectation in the
current quarter because of rising interest rates. Home Depot fell
while other retail stocks also paid a price for an anticipated
economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
Good news from Corning about its rising earnings did not
encourage investors in the volatile stock market. The fiber-optics
company said it anticipates earnings for the second quarter to go
up to 80 cents a share, well above analysts' estimates of 69 cents
per share.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 1.66 at 646.78 and the American Stock
Exchange index fell 2.72 at 942.47. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 14.55 at 508.51.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange with 1,478 down, 1,434 up and 509
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 751.95 million shares from 782.69
million in the previous session. 
</P>
