<HEADLINE> U.S. Army Leader Calls for Action to Deal With Military Suicide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"We have a serious problem with suicides," Shinseki wrote in a
message published in the latest issue of Soldiers, an Army
magazine. The matter is urgent, he said. "We must take better care
of our people."
</P>
<P>
Official statistics do not indicate any general increase in
suicides for the military as a whole, although the Army says its
suicide rate has gone up in the past two years, to one of the
highest levels since the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
In the first five days of 2000, the Army had four suspected
suicides, Shinseki said.
</P>
<P>
The Army last year had 65 confirmed suicides and 12 deaths
suspected to be suicides, a rate of 15.5 suicides per 100,000
soldiers. That rate climbed for the second year in a row and is
the highest among the services.
</P>
<P>
The Marine Corps last year had a rate of 15 suicides per 100,
000 service members, the Navy's was 11 and the Air Force was at 5.
6. 
</P>
