<HEADLINE> Israeli-Palestinian Talks to Resume in Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators will reopen peace talks here Tuesday despite the
uncertainty over the Middle East peace process triggered by the
death of Syrian President Hafez Assad.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a regular briefing here Monday, White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart said President Bill Clinton's message to
the negotiators was "that time is short, we're at a critical
moment in this process; that all of the parties need to understand
the importance of working together to bridge these remaining
differences, as difficult as they are."
</P>
<P>
The talks, the third of its kind since the beginning of the
year, is supposed to determine the future of Jerusalem and how
much land Israel will cede to the Palestinians for a state.
Refugee and water problems were also on the agenda of the talks.
</P>
<P>
The sides are still aiming to work out "a final status"
agreement to settle all major issues outstanding between Israel
and the Palestinian Authority before the September 13 deadline.
</P>
<P>
The two delegations, which have already arrived here, will
reportedly meet U.S. officials separately ahead of the resumption
of talks.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, President Clinton and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat will hold a summit on Thursday to discuss the peace
process. The summit was originally scheduled for Wednesday but
postponed due to President Assad's funeral. 
</P>
</TEXT>
