<HEADLINE> London's Millennium Bridge Closed For Weeks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 12 (Xinhua) - The swaying Millennium Bridge which
opened across London's river Thames on Saturday is to be closed to
allow engineers to carry out further safety checks.
</P>
<P>
It will be shut from 10 p.m. Monday after complaints that the
bridge "moves excessively" under the weight of thousands of
visitors. Some even complained of seasickness after crossing it.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for the Millennium Bridge Trust said it would be
"weeks rather than days" before visitors would be allowed back.
</P>
<P>
It is the first new river crossing in central London since
Tower Bridge opened in 1894 and links St. Paul's Cathedral north
of the river with the new Tate Modern and the Globe Theater in
Southwark on the south bank.
</P>
<P>
The closure was yet another embarrassing setback for London's
costly millennium projects after the loss-making Millennium Dome
and the London Eye which failed to open at the start of the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
A team from the bridge's engineers Arup started inspecting the
bridge Monday to track down the problem. It remained open to
pedestrians but the trust later announced the prolonged closure.
</P>
</TEXT>
