<HEADLINE> U.S. Gasoline Price Hits Record for Third Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The average national retail
price for unleaded gasoline hit another record high for the third
week in a row, jumping 6.8 cents from last week to 1.631 U.S.
dollars a gallon, the Energy Department reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Gasoline prices have increased nationwide in recent weeks with
the beginning of the heavy summer driving season. In some areas,
gasoline prices have skyrocketed to more than 2 dollars a gallon
in a matter of a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
The gasoline price has risen 14 cents over the last month and
was up 52 cents a gallon from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Midwest drivers continued to pay the most for fuel, with the
price for conventional gasoline up 15 cents last week to 1.796
dollars a gallon and cleaner burning reformulated gasoline up 13.7
cents to 1.972 dollars. U.S. government officials met with oil
companies on Monday to find out why fuel prices in the region are
so high.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf coast states had the cheapest fuel, up 1.1 cents a
gallon to 1.476 dollars for conventional gasoline, while
reformulated gasoline actually fell 1.2 cents to 1.472 dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
