<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia, Yemen Sign Border Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia and Yemen signed
in the western Saudi city of Jeddah on Monday a final land and sea
border agreement, following persistent bilateral efforts aimed to
close their long-running border dispute.
</P>
<P>
The deal was inked by the foreign ministers of the two Arab
neighbors, with the presence of Saudi Crown Prince and Deputy Prime
Minister Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz and visiting Yemeni President Ali
Abdullah Saleh, said a joint communique issued at the end of
Saleh's two-day official visit.
</P>
<P>
The communique said the agreement outlines border coordinates
between the two countries for territory covered by the 1934 Taif
Agreement and annexes, which granted three provinces in the border
areas to Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The joint communique said leaders of the two sides held
extensive talks on bilateral ties and expressed satisfaction over
achievements in economic, commercial and cultural fields, according
to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Saleh, who arrived in Jeddah on Sunday on his first official
visit to the Gulf kingdom in four years, met with both Saudi King
Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz and Prince Abdullah later Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Arab diplomatic sources in Saudi Arabia said the Saudi-
Yemeni talks focused on the issue of their borders demarcation.
</P>
<P>
Riyadh and Sana'a had to re-demarcate their land borders where
300 border signs had disappeared due to denudation and aging
factors.
</P>
<P>
They also needed to negotiate a settlement to the demarcation
of their maritime borders in the Red Sea.
</P>
<P>
Senior Saudi officials said earlier this year that following
several years of work of their joint committees in charge of
specifying the borders signs, most of the land border posts have
been relocated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
