<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA -- The scheduled Wednesday meeting between U.S. President
Bill Clinton and Chairman of the Palestinian National Authority
Yasser Arafat in Washington has been postponed to Thursday, a
senior Palestinian official said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to an advisor to Arafat, the one-day delay is because
that both Arafat and U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
will attend Tuesday's funeral of the late Syrian President Hafez
al-Assad, who died of heart attack last Saturday. (Arafat-Clinton-
Meeting)
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanese President Emile Lahoud has issued a withering
attack on the United Nations for its handling of the process of
verifying Israel's troop withdrawal from south Lebanon, Daily Star
newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a memorandum to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, Lahoud on
Sunday expressed "surprise" at the fact that U.N. special envoy to
the Middle East Terje Roed-Larsen had insisted on a unique "
withdrawal line" instead of demanding that Israel pull back its
troops behind the internationally-recognized borders under U.N.
resolutions 425 and 426.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud complained that U.N. cartographers had rejected an
existing and recognized border to establish a "fictitious"
withdrawal line to be used as the basis for confirmation of the
Israeli pullout.(Lebanon-Israel-Withdrawal)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Over 100 Druze residents on the Golan Heights
scuffled with Israeli police Monday morning for being unable to
enter Syria to attend Tuesday's funeral for late Syrian President
Hafez al-Assad.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of Druze people had been gathering at the Quneitra
Border Gate between Syria and the Israeli-occupied Golan Heights
since early morning, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
They were waiting for making their journey to Damascus for the
funeral of Assad, who died of heart attack Saturday at age 69.
(Israel-Syria-Scuffle)
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Six people were killed in a building collapse in
Egypt's Mediterranean port city of Alexandria, the country's Middle
East News Agency reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The six floor apartment block fell on Sunday when the building
was ordered torn down, the news agency quoted Alexandria police
chief Farouq Abbas as saying.
</P>
<P>
Three people were also injured, including a 65-year-old
bystander who was hit by falling debris and a young man who was
hurt as he tried to rescue buried residents, Abbas said. Egypt-
Building-Collapse)
</P>
<P>
