<HEADLINE> Paraguay's President Rejects Oviedo's Asylum in Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Paraguay's President Paraguay
Luis Gonzalez Macchi, considered Monday improbable that Brazil
concedes political asylum to ex-coup General, Lino Oviedo.
</P>
<P>
Gonzalez said that Paraguay will stimulate measures for
extraditing Oviedo, captured  Sunday in Brazilian city Foz de
Iguazu, according to reports coming from Asuncion, Paraguay's
capital.
</P>
<P>
Paraguayan authorities accuse Oviedo of intellectual authorship
of Vice President Luis Maria Argana's murder, carried out in
March of last year, and of the coup attempt of last month against
President Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
The leader said that Oviedo's capture, "gives us a bit of
tranquillity, and allows us to fulfill our oath that impunity will
be banished from this country".
</P>
<P>
One of Oviedo's lawyers said that Paraguay's ex army leader
will request political asylum in Brazil following his detention in
this country in order to extradite him.
</P>
<P>
The ex-coup General took asylum on March 28, 1999 in Argentina,
from where he fled headed toward an unknown destination on the eve
of this country's President, Fernando de la Rua's taking of power
December 10, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Oviedo was sentenced to 10 years in prison for a coup attempt
in 1996 and of his sentence did eight months as his friend, former
President Raul Cubas, gave him freedom.
</P>
<P>
Supreme Federal Tribunal of Brazil will decide about Oviedo's
extradition.
</P>
