<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Appeals for $378 Million to Feed Drought Victims in Horn of Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Monday
launched here an appeal for 378 million U.S. dollars to meet the
immediate needs of millions of people affected by drought in the
Horn of Africa.
</P>
<P>
The appeal constitutes food and non-food items to cater for
13.4 million people affected in Ethiopia, Kenya, Eritrea, Somalia
and Djibouti, for the period between June and December 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release by the UN Office for the
Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs, the present emergency
situation was caused by three consecutive years of poor rains and
total failure of the rains last April.
</P>
<P>
The UN appeal seeks 302 million U.S. dollars for food and
another 76 million U.S. dollars for shelter, health, water and
sanitation.
</P>
<P>
With 90 percent of the total drought affected population, the
hardest hit are Ethiopia and Kenya. Ethiopia is by far the most
affected with 10 million of its 63 million people needing
assistance, followed by Kenya, where 2.2 million people need food
aid.
</P>
<P>
Some 193.4 million U.S. dollars out of the total appeal is
believed to address the needs of affected people in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
"Timely assistance is the difference between survival and death
for a large section of the 13.4 million people, mostly women,
children and elderly persons", said Catherine Bertini, UN special
Envoy for the Drought in the Greater Horn of Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
