<HEADLINE> South African Plane Crashes in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- A South African plane has crashed
into the Zambezi River killing two pilots on the spot after it hit
a pylon in western Zambia, Zambian News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The incident happened at Likanda area in Katimamulilo, Western
Province, on Saturday afternoon when two tourist planes headed for
Maziba Bay in Zambia for a holiday from Livingstone. One of them
flying at a very low level along the Zambezi River suddenly hit
into the pylon and lost its propeller and two wheels before it
fell into the river.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to retrieve the plane have failed due to lack of
special equipments to identify exactly where the plane is on the
river bed. The report did not say whether there were other
passengers on the plane.
</P>
<P>
The District Administrator, Robert Sipilanyambe, has confirmed
the incident. Meanwhile, Zambia Revenue Authority in conjunction
with the police have tried in vain the whole of Sunday to locate
the plane using a boat.
</P>
<P>
Reinforcement is expected from Namibia on Monday with more
divers and a bulldozer. 
</P>
