<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Kenya, Uganda to Sign Communication Cooperation Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 12 (Xinhua) -- A memorandum of understanding
for strengthening cooperations among South African, Kenyan and
Ugandan communications departments is being drafted, South African
Communications Ministry announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to Communications Minister Ivy Matsepe-Casaburri, who
has just returned from a five-day working trip to the two east
African countries, the memorandum can serve as the basis for
boosting cooperation in post, telecommunications and broadcasting
sectors to enhance business and investment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Matsepe-Casaburri described her meetings with her Kenyan
counterpart W.N. Mudavadi and the Ugandan Minister of Works,
Housing and Communications John Nasasira as "extremely fruitful".
</P>
<P>
Kenya is South Africa's largest trading partner on the
continent, while Uganda is another important economic player.
</P>
<P>
Among key issues to be included in the memorandum are
connectivity in Africa, collaboration between policy-makers and
regulators, rural communication, staff exchange programs, human
resource development and training and postal security. 
