<HEADLINE> Ugandan Central Bank Intervenes in Currency Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Uganda, the country's
central bank, intervened Monday in the foreign exchange market on
the sale side to the tune of 10 million U.S. dollars, according to
a press release from the bank.
</P>
<P>
The Monday's action brings total intervention on the sale side
to 98.5 million U.S. dollars since January this year, said the
release.
</P>
<P>
"The bank continues to monitor closely developments in the
foreign exchange market and will not hesitate to intervene when
necessary," the release added.
</P>
<P>
The local currency on Sunday was traded at 1,635 shillings
against the dollar, from an average of 1,555 shillings earlier
last week.
</P>
<P>
Analysts have blamed the shilling's depreciation on poor
exports, especially coffee, Uganda's major foreign exchange
earner.
</P>
<P>
However, the clashes between Ugandan and Rwandan troops in
Kisangani, a city in the Democratic Republic of the Congo, in the
last few days was also blamed for the pressure on the shilling.
</P>
</TEXT>
