<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shas Minister's Comments Stir Israeli Political Spectrum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 12 (Xinhua) -- An ultra-Orthodox Israeli
minister drew wide criticism at home for his comments relating one
of his cabinet colleagues and an anti-religious party with Nazism.
</P>
<P>
Sholomo Benizri, health minister from the religious ultra-
Orthodox Shas party, on Monday accused Education Minister Yossi
Sarid of incitement against his Shas party, which he compared with
Nazis' incitement against the Jews during the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
Benizri pinned the Education Ministry's opposition to more
funding for the almost bankrupt religious education network run by
Shas on Sarid's "blind hatred" of Shas.
</P>
<P>
The funding issue has exacerbated the current government crisis,
with 17 Knesset (parliament) members of the Shas threatening the
coalition government, of which Shas is the second biggest partner,
with their votes last week in the Knesset preliminary reading for
an opposition bill calling for early parliamentary election.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Benizri also termed Yosef Lapid, leader of the
anti-religious Shinui Party, as a "Super Haider," referring to the
Austrian extreme-rightist politician Joerg Haider notorious for his
sympathetic remarks about Hitler and Nazism.
</P>
<P>
Benizri's comments have invited fierce criticism from across
Israel's political spectrum as well as from the Yad Vashem
Holocaust Memorial in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Ehud Barak swiftly condemned Benizri's
provocative remarks, saying that despite political differences,
there is no place for the Holocaust to be dragged into a political
debate. The prime minister also appealed for restraint and
tolerance.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Likud party, which sided with Shas in voting for
the early-election bill, also denounced Benizri's comments. Likud's
caucus whip Reuven Rivlin chided Benizri of "lack of knowledge
about the Holocaust."
</P>
<P>
The Yad Vashem Holocaust Memorial in Jerusalem has also
criticized the lippy Shas minister. It protested that the
Holocaust, during which 6 million Jews were killed by the German
Nazis during the World War II, was being exploited by politics and
called on all politicians to stop.
</P>
<P>
The furor came against the backdrop of the ongoing coalition
crisis in the Jewish state. Shas, the third largest party in the
Knesset after Barak's One Israel Party and Likud, hardened its
positions in negotiations with the ruling One Israel.
</P>
<P>
One Israel charges that Shas has backtracked on their latest
agreements. Following the Knesset vote on the early-election bill,
Barak has been trying to keep Shas in the coalition on condition
that Shas will withdraw its support for the bill in future votings.
</P>
<P>
Shas officials agreed that they have altered their prior
positions and want more of a say in the Middle East peace process
and domestic social issues.
</P>
<P>
Barak has reportedly been ready to allocate 25 million shekels
(6 million U.S. dollars) to cover Shas' educational deficit. Shas
was annoyed by Sarid's left-wing Meretz Party due to Sarid's
refusal to fund Shas' educational network unless it improves its
inefficient management and fires corrupt officials.
</P>
<P>
Shas is also demanding that its private radio stations be
granted broadcasting licenses.
</P>
<P>
Benizri said Shas' vote for last week's bill was a warning
signal. "If it does not work, Shas will bolt the coalition."
</P>
<P>
In a bid to assuage the coalition bustup, Minister in Prime
Minister's Office Haim Ramon is seeking an urgent meeting with Shas
spiritual leader Ovadia Yosef, who has the final say in Shas
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Under the Transition Law, Barak has until Tuesday to decide
whether to carry out his earlier threat to fire the defecting
ministers from the Shas party, the National Religious Party and
Yisrael Ba'aliya party who voted for the early-elections bill last
week.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of the frustration in the Knesset last week, Barak
has decided to form a new coalition similar to the existing one
instead of a narrow one without the maverick ruling partners who
voted for the early-elections bill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
