<HEADLINE> Zeus' Throne Made of Gold and Ivory, Says Greek Archeology Professor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The throne of Zeus, father of gods,
was made from gold and ivory and was built in the 8th century BC,
a Greek archaeology professor said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Professor Yiannis Sakelarakis reached the conclusion, based on
the findings of archaeological excavations conducted at Mount
Psiloritis in the southern Greek island of Crete, the Macedonian
Press Agency (MPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
At the archaeological site of Ideon Andron, Professor
Sakelarakis found small ivory pieces, and he believed that many of
the ivory pieces belonged to a glorious throne made of gold and
ivory that was inside the cave temple.
</P>
<P>
It is believed to be a significant archaeological finding that
reveals another aspect of the worship in ancient Crete. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Meets on DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Monday began a closed-door session to discuss the latest
developments in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), where
Ugandan and Rwandan troops were engaged in armed conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The Council meeting came after U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan condemned the "reckless, senseless" fighting between Ugandan
and Rwandan forces in the DRC city of Kisangani and said that he
would ask the 15-nation Security Council to take steps to end it.
</P>
<P>
The Monday meeting also took place after both Uganda and
Rwanda announced over the weekend the withdrawal of their troops
from the northeastern city in the central African country.
</P>
<P>
Uganda said Sunday its forces had withdrawn from their
positions in Kisangani after a week of fighting with Rwandan
troops there. On the same day, Rwanda announced that it was
withdrawing from Kisangani after calm returned to the war-torn
city of Kisangani following the heavy clashes.
</P>
<P>
U.N. observers in Kisangani said that the Ugandans had pulled
back to the northern side of the Tshopo river bridge Saturday
night, marking a drastic shift of the urban front line dividing
the two armies.
</P>
<P>
Since close allies began a broader war against DRC President
Laurent Kabila nearly two years ago, Uganda and Rwanda have turned
their guns on one another.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Mission in the DRC, known as the MONUC, currently
comprises about 130 military observers and support staff. They
include 20 observers in Kisangani who are now being reinforced and
located with both the Ugandan and Rwandan troops.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council on February 24 authorized the increasing
force to 500 military observers and some 5,000 soldiers to protect
them and provide logistics. But Annan has not yet been able to
certify that security and other conditions permit them to be
deployed in the country, formerly known as Zaire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
