<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Meets on Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The U.N. force was established through Security Council
Resolution 186 of 1964 with the mandate to prevent a recurrence of
fighting between the Greek Cypriot and Turkish Cypriot communities.
</P>
<P>
Following the hostilities of 1974, the Council adopted a number
of resolutions expanding the mandate of the UNFICYP to include
supervising a de facto cease-fire and maintaining a buffer zone
between the lines of the Cyprus National Guard and of the Turkish
Cypriot forces
</P>
<P>
In the absence of a political settlement to the Cyprus problem,
the UNFICYP continues its presence on the island.
</P>
<P>
Under the current circumstances, the presence of the UNFICYP "
remains indispensable" for the maintenance of the cease-fire
between the two sides, said Annan. The UNFICYP now has over 1,200
troops.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the developments in the past six months, he said the
situation along the crease-fire lines was stable and noted an
increase of contacts between Greek and Turkish Cypriots and the
decision by the Turkish side to lift measures affecting travel.
</P>
<P>
Annan's proposal came before the third round of proximity talks
between the Turkish Cypriot and the Greek Cypriot communities
begins in Geneva in early July.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, an eastern Mediterranean island country, has been
divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled north and the Greek
Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of an
abortive pro-Athens military coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has tried to reunite the island but talks
between the two communities have produced no tangible results.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish side has maintained that the only way out of the
issue is to establish a confederation on the basis of two states,
an idea rejected by the Greek state and the international
community at large. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Consumers Face Price Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Britain's service sector is growing
strongly and providers of services to consumers plan to raise
their prices sharply over the next three months, according to a
business survey published Monday.
</P>
<P>
The survey by the Confederation of British Industry (CBI) shows
the first rise in confidence among consumer-services firms since
September which is regarded as a sign of lifting prices.
</P>
<P>
The CBI's quarterly survey said that a balance of 39 percent of
consumer-services firms plan to raise their prices over the next
three months, more than double the 19 percent three months ago.
</P>
<P>
Roger Bootle, an adviser to Delotte's, said: "If the prices of
consumer services rise over the next three months at the sharp
rate indicated in the survey, it would probably be a concern to
the Bank of England."
</P>
<P>
The Bank's monetary policy committee has highlighted strongly
rising service-sector prices in its recent discussions.
</P>
<P>
However, the CBI said that overall, the message of the survey
is that growth was "fairly" stable and is so far not creating
inflationary pressure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
