<HEADLINE> U.N. Mission Attacked in DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. personnel in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) narrowly escaped injury when
their offices were attacked at the weekend by a stone-throwing mob,
a U.N. spokesman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Spokesman Fred Eckhard told a news conference that "a
series of violent demonstrations took place outside the U.N.
mission headquarters in Kinshasa," the capital of the DRC.
</P>
<P>
"Several U.N. vehicles were damaged and staff narrowly escaped
injury as protesters threw stones at the building, smashing some
of the windows," he said.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press here Monday, the president of
the Security Council, Jean-David Levitte of France, said that
members of the Council "expressed concern at violent
demonstrations before MONUC (the U.N. Mission in the DRC)
Headquarters and recalled the responsibility of the DRC Government
to ensure the security of MONUC."  
</P>
