<HEADLINE> Bomb Blast Could Affect S. African Tourism: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The car-bomb explosion
outside a popular restaurant in Cape Town on Saturday night could
affect tourism in South Africa, Cape Town tourism manager Sheryl
Ozinsky said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said every bomb blast and every incident of crime affected
tourism and the confidence of visitors.
</P>
<P>
"We are appalled at the latest incident. Thank God no one was
badly injured," Ozinsky said. "We really need to get these
perpetrators behind bars."
</P>
<P>
Two people, including a five-year-old child, were treated for
shock when the device detonated outside New York Bagels and Sit-in
Deli Restaurant around 8:00 p.m. on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Police have established that the car, a red Toyota Corolla, in
which the bomb had been placed, had been hijacked in Diepriver on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
On that day two men robbed a 33-year-old man of his car when he
stopped in Ruchill Street around 8:00 p.m.
</P>
<P>
The motorist had been closely questioned by police but was
unable to identify the hijackers as they wore masks.
</P>
<P>
Several witnesses have given police information about the blast
but investigators remain in the dark about possible motives for
the attack. 
</P>
