<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Illegal Aliens Apply for Resident Permits in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESUBURG, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Illegal aliens have flooded
the South African Home Affairs Department with residence permit
applications since a Constitutional Court ruling suspended certain
sections of the Aliens Control Act last year.
</P>
<P>
Briefing a parliament committee on proposed amendments to the
Act, home affairs legal officer David Ramagalela said Monday the
court's suspension of article 25 (9)(b) of the act had effectively
forced his department to issue immigration papers to thousands of
foreigners married to South Africans.
</P>
<P>
Many of the foreigners had not been married to South African
spouses at the time they entered the country, but were now able to
apply for residence permits under the terms of last year's ruling,
Ramagalela said.
</P>
<P>
While many of the illegal foreigners were suspected of being
involved in illegal activities, it was difficult to refuse a
permit on the basis of unproven allegations, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Constitutional Court last year ruled that some of the
provisions of the Aliens Control Act infringed on the right of
South Africans who were married to foreigners to live with their
spouses.
</P>
<P>
Constitutional Court Judge Kate O'Regan noted in her ruling
last year that the act allowed no automatic right to a residence
permit, but required that each application be considered on merit.
</P>
<P>
O'Regan said the past practice had forced South Africans who
were married to foreign spouses to either go abroad with their
partners, or remain behind alone, pending the outcome of the
application.
</P>
<P>
The committee is trying to introduce amendments to the act
which will justify the refusal of a temporary residence permit.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, committee members -- with the exception of the
Democratic Party -- voted in favor of the Identification Amendment
Bill, which provides for the cessation of all forms of
identification except bar-coded green ID books. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola on Alert of Possible Food Crisis in Central Highland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Angola's health services have
warned that there could be a food crisis in the next three months
in the country's central highland, especially in Huambo Province,
following the reduction of international aid, the official news
agency Angop reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The humanitarian aid including the basic necessities
distributed by the World Food Program (WFP) to the central Huambo
Province has been reduced by 75 percent since May which the health
services said was the main cause of the food crisis in Huambo, a
province that suffered the most fierce civil conflicts in the past
25 years.
</P>
<P>
The crisis could affect over 1.6 million people, with the
300,000 displaced persons living in the central highland being the
hardest hit victims, said the health services.
</P>
<P>
The reduction of the humanitarian aid to Huambo is due to an
accord between the Huambo provincial government and the WFP, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
But some non-governmental organizations (NGO) considered the
accord as " extemporary" and would lead to a "totally ruined"
result.
</P>
<P>
The Representative of an Italian NGO said that the next three
months could be "dark" in terms of food security for the
population living in Huambo, adding that it is worrying that the
WFP reduced the aid from 4,000 tons to 1,100 tons per month to
Huambo in a period without good perspective in agricultural
production.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, 57 children in the central hospital of
Huambo died of malnutrition from January to May, while other 366
are being treated in the hospital. During the same period,
nutritional centers in the Huambo City, capital of the province,
have lodged 9,560 children suffering from malnutrition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
