<HEADLINE> New IBM Notebook to Use Linux </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The ThinkPad notebook from IBM, the world's largest computer
maker, will come with Linux software from Caldera Systems Inc.
beginning in the third quarter, reported Bloomberg News Sunday.
</P>
<P>
It is the latest stage of IBM's plan to support the operating
systems. The company has altered its computers to run Linux over
the last 12 months, whose popularity has increased among users at
Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
IBM will promote the ThinkPad for use by software developers,
students and Web technicians, who like to be on the leading edge
of the Internet era.
</P>
<P>
In addition, IBM will spend 6 million U.S. dollars to help
software developers create applications that run on Linux. But the
company said IBM was not trying to distance itself from Microsoft
and would continue to support Microsoft, the world's largest
software maker. 
