<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey is taking advantage of its rich geothermal
resources for heating and other purposes.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Energy and Natural Resources Cumhur Ersumer, who
attended the World Geothermal Congress in Japan, said that Turkey
is ranked the fifth among the countries using geothermal energy for
heating and is expected to become the first in 2010.
</P>
<P>
The next conference will be held in 2005 in Antalya, Turkey's
Mediterranean port city in the southwest.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Demand for assembled and compact PCs is expected to
grow rapidly in the United Arab Emirates (UAE) as Dubai prepares to
make information technology its engine of growth.
</P>
<P>
More than 1.4 million PC units were shipped to the Middle East
and North Africa region last year and the recent policy initiatives
in Dubai, Egypt and Bahrain will push overall sales further.
</P>
<P>
An ongoing IT exhibition, staged at the Dubai World Trade
Center, is a clear indication of the increasing use of personal
computers and the subscriber base for the Internet, which is
currently estimated at 160,000.
</P>
<P>
The UAE has registered remarkable growth in the use of Internet,
which is bound to result in incremental PC and accessory sales in
the long run, especially when shopping online and other virtual
activities become a normal day-to-day activity.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Arab investment in Egypt stood at 3.92 billion U.S.
dollars at the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Arab countries have set up 1,799 companies and joint ventures in
Egypt by 1999, which have a total registered capital of 16.28
billion dollars, Chairman of Egypt's General Authority of Free Zone
and Investment Mohammed el-Ghamrawi said.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia is the biggest investor among the Arab countries
with 1.22 billion dollars, followed by Kuwait with 1.02 billion
dollars and the United Arab Emirates with about 380 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Over 100,000 tons of Egyptian cotton have been
contracted for export to 35 countries at 220 million dollars since
the beginning of the export season last September, Chairman of the
Egyptian Cotton Export Union Saeed Haggag said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
So far, about 76 percent of the cotton has been shipped to the
destinations, Haggag said.
</P>
<P>
Italy led the importers with 23,500 tons, followed by Turkey
with 11,700 tons, India 10,000 tons and the United States 9,950
tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
