<HEADLINE> India Reiterates Support for Sri Lanka's Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Indian External Minister
Jaswant Singh Monday reiterated India's support for the unity,
sovereignty and territorial integrity of Sri Lanka which has been
troubled by an upsurge in the long-running civil war.
</P>
<P>
Singh made clear India's stand during his discussions with Sri
Lankan President Kumaratunga and Foreign Minister Kadirgamar, said
a Sri Lanka-India joint statement released at the end of Singh's
two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
The statement said Singh expressed "the continued commitment of
the Government of India to the unity, sovereignty and territorial
integrity of Sri Lanka."
</P>
<P>
He also conveyed the good wishes and support of the Indian
government to the restoration of a lasting peace through a
possible political process which would result in a settlement
satisfactory to all communities.
</P>
<P>
Singh is the first Indian minister to visit Sri Lanka since
April when the civil war flared up between government troops and
the separatist rebels of Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE).
</P>
<P>
President Kumaratunga apprised Singh of the current war
situation and political developments, including the consultations
between the government and other political parties and the
facilitation efforts of Norway.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga welcomed India's offer to be of assistance in the
humanitarian as well as economic sphere to ease and constraints
that may be currently faced by Sri Lanka, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
India has ruled out military involvement in the island nation's
civil war which the LTTE rebels are fighting for a separate
homeland for minority Tamils in the island's north and east since
1983.
</P>
<P>
However, India has been in close contact with the Sri Lankan
government and promised brokering peace and humanitarian
assistance if asked.
</P>
<P>
Singh brought a credit amounting to 100 million U.S. dollars
from India during this visit, as well as the possibilities of Sri
Lanka's purchasing wheat, rice and sugar on a counter trade basis
from India.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Singh also met opposition leader Ranil
Wickremesinghe as well as representatives from other political
parties.
</P>
<P>
Singh, who came here Sunday afternoon, is scheduled to return
to New Delhi Monday evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
