<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Microsoft Helps Train Layoffs in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- One hundred and twenty laid off
workers and 40 training assistants from re-employment centers
graduated recently from a 6-month training program sponsored by
Microsoft from the United States.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that a multinational company
participated in training and re-employment programs of laid off
workers in the northeast China city of Dalian.
</P>
<P>
Liu Fengming, deputy general manager of Microsoft (China), said
that the company will also provide funding and training support
for similar programs in western China later this year.
</P>
<P>
Dalian Vice Mayor Wang Chengmin said that the government needs
help from all sectors of the country to address the problems of
laid off workers. The Dalian Labor Bureau has carried out training
program with funds from Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
He said that the IT Training Program is designed to expand laid
off workers' options for re-employment and meet the real
expectations of today's labor market.
</P>
<P>
"We are glad to see that many trainees of this program have
gone on to achieve individual success," he said.
</P>
<P>
The trainees received computer training and participated in
internship programs with local businesses to gain hands-on work
experience. Some 80 percent of the laid off workers have found new
jobs through the program.
</P>
<P>
There are 60,000 laid off workers in Dalian. The 40 training
assistants graduating from the program will work in twelve re-
employment training centers and train 1,200 laid off workers every
year.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft also donated 100 licenses for Microsoft Office
software to the Dalian Labor Bureau to use at the re-employment
training centers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
