<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Filipino Workers Deployed Abroad in 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The number of Filipino workers
deployed overseas grew by about one percent in the first quarter,
and the number is expected to further increase in the months ahead
because of the extended armed conflict in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Ernesto Herrera, a lawmaker of the House of Representatives,
said Monday that 230,310 workers were deployed overseas from
January to March this year, or 1,886 more than the 228,424
deployed over the same period of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Herrera, meanwhile, said the raging armed conflict in Mindanao
would force more Filipinos to seek employment overseas.
</P>
<P>
To help ease unemployment in Mindanao, Herrera urged the
agencies responsible for rehabilitation work in strife-torn areas
to give priority employment to residents displaced from their
homes and livelihood.
</P>
<P>
"Labor-intensive rehabilitation projects, particularly those
involving the restoration of damaged public infrastructure, should
be encouraged to provide emergency employment to evacuees,"
Herrera said.
</P>
<P>
Labor officials earlier predicted an increase in unemployment
in Mindanao because of the continuing military offensives against
the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF).
</P>
<P>
The offensive on MILF positions have caused the evacuation of
at least 500,000 civilians since April 27, when the military
launched attacks on rebel encampments along the Narciso Ramos
Highway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to File Charges Against Virus Author </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Monday it will file charges against suspected computer hacker Onel
de Guzman before June 15 to formally end its month-long probe on
the tagged author of the "I Love You" virus.
</P>
<P>
Federico Opinion, director of the National Bureau of
Investigation(NBI), said this will give enough time for
authorities to indict Guzman in court before President Joseph
Estrada's scheduled trip to the United States in July.
</P>
<P>
According to Opinion, the president might be grilled by the
American press during his visit to the United States due to the
absence of Philippine laws to prosecute cyber crimes following the
proliferation of the "Love Bug" virus.
</P>
<P>
The damage caused by the virus is estimated to be in the
billions of U.S. dollars after it infected millions of computers
around the world starting May 4.
</P>
<P>
The virus was later traced to the Philippines, particularly to
the house of Guzman's family in Manila. The NBI raided the Guzman
residence on May 8.
</P>
<P>
Opinion said the charges t be filed against Guzman might
include theft, malicious mischief, and violation of the credit
card law.
</P>
<P>
"The charges are still under study. This is a combined legal
study by the Department of Justice and the NBI to ensure an
airtight case against Guzman," said Opinion.
</P>
<P>
The NBI is basing its charges against Guzman on his graduation
thesis proposal which was rejected. In his proposal, he reportedly
described the virus. The NBI is also basing its case on the fact
that virus attack was traced to his house's phone number. 
</P>
</TEXT>
