<HEADLINE> Somali Militiamen Launch Mutiny Against Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The loud noise of heavy machine
guns and assault rifles could be heard on Sunday night around the
former presidential palace in central Mogadishu, which is now
resided by faction leader Hussein Mohamed Aidid.
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses said there had been an exchange of fire between
mutineers and loyalists of Aidid near the residence of their
master.
</P>
<P>
There was no word of casualties over the fighting on Sunday
night, however, there had been some damage to the walls of
buildings around the area where the fighting took place.
</P>
<P>
The fighting is a result of a mutiny, which has been brewing
among the militiamen since the beginning of this month, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
According to the local daily Qaran published on Monday, the
mutineers are complaining about lack of proper care from Aidid.
</P>
<P>
The militiamen were quoted as saying they had not been paid for
a long time and not given adequate food or medical care.
</P>
<P>
There has been no word as yet from Hussein Aidid himself over
the fighting and his relation with the militiamen.
</P>
<P>
The mutineers looted the former presidential palace four days
ago, taking away ammunition, furniture and everything they could
lay their hands on, in protest against Aidid's treatment towards
them. 
