<HEADLINE> Thousands of Artifacts Found in Chongqing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Local residents in Beibei District
of Chongqing Municipality have found thousands of stone artifacts
near a stream.
</P>
<P>
The articles include porcelain, earthenware, axes, stone knives,
bone knives and mammal teeth, the "People's Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Zou Houxi, chief of the excavation team with the Chongqing
Museum, said that the artifacts date back to the Shang (16th- 11th
BC) and Zhou (11th- 221 BC) dynasties.
</P>
<P>
The artifacts belong to one or two cultural ruins on the upper
reaches of the stream, which is a small tributary of the Yangtze
River, said Zou.
</P>
<P>
Liu Yuchuan, the museum's curator, said that modern people
living in the district often found such kind of precious stone
articles in recent years. 
</P>
