<HEADLINE> Anti-Budget General Strike Observed in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Countrywide anti-budget general
strike called by the combined opposition was observed almost
peacefully Monday, partially disrupting daily life and business.
</P>
<P>
The four-party opposition alliance comprising the Bangladesh
Nationalist Party, Jatiya Party, Jamaat-e-Islami and Islami Oikya
Jote (Islami Solidarity Front), called for the dawn-to-dusk
shutdown against what they said government's "anti-people budget
for 2000-2001."
</P>
<P>
In the capital, though most of the shops and offices were
closed, some shops, particularly hardware stores, offices and
banks were seen open under half shutter.
</P>
<P>
People were seen moving from one place to another boarding
various modes of vehicles, including state-run and private buses.
</P>
<P>
Government offices were in operation with comparatively thin
attendance. Educational institutions were closed during the strike.
</P>
<P>
Pro-strike activists brought out processions in different parts
of the capital. However, there was no report of any untoward
incident.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Shah AMS Kibria last Thursday placed a
national budget of 8.5 billion U.S. dollars for fiscal 2000-2001
in the parliament, showing an overall deficit of 3.7 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister proposed to meet the big deficit from
foreign grants and loans, domestic sources and from bank
borrowings.
</P>
<P>
The Federation of Bangladesh Chambers of Commerce and Industry
(FBCCI) has expressed concern at deteriorating fiscal deficit and
higher borrowings by the government from banking sector. In its
initial reaction on the budget, FBCCI said on Sunday that
borrowing by the government will crowd out the private sector from
settling funds from the banks.
</P>
<P>
FBCCI also expressed its concern over the fact that the budget
does not provide definite guideline for creation of employment
opportunities and growth of manufacturing sector.
</P>
<P>
However, FBCCI appreciated the new budget for providing
incentives for capital market development, relief for the small
tax payers, widening the tax-net and further streamlining the tax
administration.
</P>
<P>
It also hailed increased allocation for education and healthy
sectors and further strengthening of special measures addressing
poor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
