<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consultative Group on Mozambique Successful: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Finance Minister Luisa
Diogo has commended the World Bank's Consultative Group meeting on
Mozambique held in Paris last Thursday and Friday as "very well".
</P>
<P>
In addition to the financial pledges made, the meeting also
reached the consensus that under the current conditions Mozambique
will have difficulty in attaining a two-digit economic growth if
there are no changes in certain areas, she was quoted by Monday's
independent newsheet Metical as saying.
</P>
<P>
Diogo listed the infrastructure of the economy, agricultural
policy and regional imbalance as some of the areas that need
reforms and improvement.
</P>
<P>
There was consensus that there must be "improved performance in
these areas in order to step up the rate of growth", she said.
</P>
<P>
The Consultative Group meeting brings together all Mozambique's
major international partners, and is the forum where the financing
needs of the economy are discussed.
</P>
<P>
According to Diogo, donors and funding agencies gathering in
Paris had promised to offer 530 million U.S. dollars (75 percent
in grants and 25 percent in soft loans) to Mozambique this year,
more than the 504 million dollars requested by the Mozambican
government.
</P>
<P>
Diogo said, the Paris meeting gave "indicative figures" of 560
million dollars in 2001, of which 75 to 80 percent will be in the
form of grants. The figure is also more than the 514 million
dollars mentioned in the government's document submitted to the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
"There were no deep divergences among the country's foreign
partners," the minister said, noting that "the main differences
were in how to implement the recommendations."
</P>
<P>
"Some of the Nordic countries were in favor of strengthening
direct funding for the budget. Others stressed a sectoral
approach. Others thought that, before embracing the model of
increased direct funding for the budget, there must be
improvements in budgetary management," she said.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican government is in favour of a gradual approach,
increasing direct funding for the budget "as we improve the
management of the budget", she said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also recommended that the government should
increase the amount of taxes collected while reducing tax rates,
she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
