<HEADLINE> Philippines, U.S. to Hold Naval Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines and the United
States will conduct a two-week naval exercise starting on
Wednesday, the second war games to be held this year, the
Philippine military said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The first called Balikatan (shoulder to shoulder) exercise,
involving close to 5,000 troops from both countries, was held in
February in various parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Navy said in a statement that the Philippine and
U.S. navies will participate in the naval war games dubbed as "
Cooperation Afloat Readiness and Training 2000."
</P>
<P>
The training exercise which is authorized under the Visiting
Forces Agreement, is designed to promote inter-operability between
U.S. and Philippine forces in the areas of operational planning
command and control, tactics and community relations projects.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,700 U.S. troops will participate in the two-week naval
maneuver. At least five American naval ships will also take part
in the war games.
</P>
<P>
On the Philippine side, about 1,500 troops and four ships will
participate in the war games, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
It is the first phase in a series of combined exercises which
the United States will conduct in the Pacific. The Americans will
also hold naval exercises with Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia,
Singapore and Thailand later this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
