<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Rejects Larsen's Border Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Emile Lahoud has
issued a withering attack on the United Nations for its handling of
the process of verifying Israel's troop withdrawal from south
Lebanon, Daily Star newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a memorandum to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, Lahoud on
Sunday expressed "surprise" at the fact that U.N. special envoy to
the Middle East Terje Roed-Larsen had insisted on a unique "
withdrawal line" instead of demanding that Israel pull back its
troops behind the internationally-recognized borders under U.N.
resolutions 425 and 426.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud complained that U.N. cartographers had rejected an
existing and recognized border to establish a "fictitious"
withdrawal line to be used as the basis for confirmation of the
Israeli pullout.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud based his complaints on the references to the "
internationally-recognized borders" under U.N. Resolution 425 of
1978 and Annan's May 22 report on the implementation of the
resolution.
</P>
<P>
Annan's report based the line on the Anglo-French border of
1923, later confirmed by the 1949 Armistice Agreement.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud's objections centered on Larsen's apparent decision to
deviate from Annan's instructions and issue what has become known
as "Larsen's line."
</P>
<P>
"Lebanon submitted the 1923 and 1949 documents and all maps
adopted for these borders, which leave no room for doubt regarding
their accuracy and authenticity, while no counter evidence was
submitted," Lahoud said in his five-page memo.
</P>
<P>
He also attacked a U.N. assertion that it was not responsible
for demarcating international boundaries. He said that Larsen's
withdrawal line had left a "dangerous vagueness" over the true
demarcation of the border.
</P>
<P>
The inspection teams moved slowly, covering some 20 kilometers
before ending at Maroun Ras on Sunday evening. The slow progress in
verifying the border has pushed back plans for deploying U.N.
peacekeepers in south Lebanon, vacated by Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
For fear of escalated Lebanese guerrilla attacks and mounting
casualties, Israel completed its troop withdrawal on May 24, ending
22-year occupation in south Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
