<HEADLINE> Share Prices Close Higher in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed in Tokyo Monday,
helped mainly by bargain-hunting of institutional investors, with
the benchmark Nikkei index turning upward for the first time in
five trading days.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose 118.70 points, or 0.70
percent from last Friday's close to end at 16,980.61.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX) which covers
all First Section issues, however, dropped 0.98 point or 0.06
percent to 1,585.83.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section decreased to 701.30 million
shares from last Friday's 1,104.46 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Shintom was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
High-priced information and technology issues were mixed, after
New York's Nasdaq composite index gained 49.28 points to 3,874.84
last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Low- and medium-priced issues continued to draw buying, with
the marine transportation, mining and shipbuilding sectors up.
</P>
<P>
Biotechnology-related issues were also up, as new investment
trusts focusing on biotech issues are scheduled to be launched
later this week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, declining issues included rubber makers, banks,
electric power and gas firms.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, gainers outnumbered
losers 843 to 451, with 105 issues closing unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
