<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel and the Palestinians have reached an understanding
that Israel will free all 1,650 Palestinian security prisoners once
the two sides agree on an outline for a final peace treaty, chief
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat said on Sunday, before leaving
for negotiations set to resume on Tuesday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Israel has not given the Palestinian National Authority a
definite answer yet, a Palestinian source close to the negotiations
said. "It seems that they do not want to release any more prisoners
until we sign the framework agreement," he added.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak sent a message of
reassurance to Syria on Sunday that Israel has no intention of
using the transition period in Damascus to stir up trouble in
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Barak also asked their ministers to refrain from commenting
publicly on the transition of power, lest their comments have a
disruptive influence on Damascus.
</P>
<P>
Noting that so far the transition of power is going smoothly in
Syria, Barak said that he and U.S. President Bill Clinton agreed
that it is unlikely that there will be a quick resumption of the
Israeli-Syrian peace negotiations, at least until Bashar al-Assad
has consolidated his power.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel's Histadrut labor federation chairman Amir Peretz
called off a general strike slated for Monday after Finance
Minister Avraham Shochat said he would freeze legislation on three
items of the tax reform package and begin talks with the union on
the provisions that it opposes.
</P>
<P>
The three clauses in question are the taxes on interest from
hitherto tax-free supplemental educational funds, tax credits for
night-shift workers, and the half-point tax credit for working
women.
</P>
<P>
Peretz told a 3,000-strong rally he is still suspicious of
Shochat, who acted after intense pressure from Prime Minister Ehud
Barak to avoid the nationwide strike.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- The Israeli religious ultra-Orthodox Shas party hardened its
position on Sunday in negotiations with Prime Minister Ehud Barak
to resolve the coalition crisis, demanding not only more money for
its school system but more of a say in the peace process and social
issues.
</P>
<P>
Barak was working against the clock to find a coalition solution
without having to dismiss six ministers from the three parties that
voted last Wednesday for a bill to dissolve the Knesset
(Parliament) and hold early elections. The bill passed its
preliminary reading.
</P>
<P>
Based on a clause in the Transition Law, Barak has until Tuesday
night to decide whether to fire the ministers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
