<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNG Not to Interfere in Solomons Affairs: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Papua New Guinea's Foreign
Minister John Kaputin issued a statement Monday pledging that his
country would not allow its territory to be used as a base for
hostile attacks against neighboring countries or for interference
in their internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, faxed to the Canberra Branch of
Xinhua from PNG Prime Minister's Office, the foreign minister made
it clear that "the PNG government respects the sovereignty of
other countries, and expects other countries to respect Papua New
Guinea's in return. We will not tolerate illegal activities by
individuals or groups who behave without proper regard for the
mutual respect between states which is the basis of national
security and peace in our region."
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister was commenting on an earlier report saying
that Papua New Guinea's Bougainville Revolutionary Army (BRA) on
Sunday took over the neighboring Solomon Islands' Choiseul and
Gizo islands to protect their allies, the Isatabu Freedom Movement
in the Guadalcanal island, with whom they have bloody ties.
</P>
<P>
The BRA fought a nine-year war to separate the Bougainville
island from PNG until a cease fire in 1998. There is suspicion of
a plan to establish a new race-based country by Bougainville and
some islands from Solomon Islands.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Minister said after a meeting with Bougainville
People's Congress President Joseph Kabui that "I have been told
that their leaders have said they are strongly opposed to
activities across the common border which might compromise the
sovereignty and security of our good neighbors in Solomon Islands.
"
</P>
<P>
Kaputin directed to investigate the origins of the media
reports, while calling on the media to display care and
responsibility in reporting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
