<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estrada Vows to Make Lasting Peace in Mindanao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
expressed anew Monday his desire to make just and lasting peace
his administration's legacy to Mindanao, along with prosperity and
development to the once-neglected region.
</P>
<P>
The president said this means extending the hand of friendship
and peace to rebel groups, but also implementing the resolve to
crush any mockery of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"We are willing to extend our hands in friendship and in peace.
But it must be an honorable and lasting peace. This is the legacy
I want to leave behind when I finish my term (in 2004) so we can
rebuild Mindanao and fulfill its promise," he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Estrada stressed that the Armed Forces of the Philippines and
the Philippine National Police share his commitment to work
towards this lasting peace, "at all costs."
</P>
<P>
He added this is the reason he rejected a 40-day ceasefire with
the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) as proposed by some "well-
meaning citizens," saying that what he wants is not a temporary,
fragile peace but a just and permanent one.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the president declined to call off military operations
against the MILF, saying his government cannot allow the rebels to
make a mockery of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He noted these groups continue to attempt to assume control
over certain parts of the country, terrorizing citizens in the
process.
</P>
<P>
"I do not want our people whether in Mindanao or elsewhere in
this country to live in fear. We can no longer allow fear and
violence to prevail," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to live under one flag, one nation, one
constitution, one government, and one Armed Forces of the
Philippines," he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
