<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NEWSMAKER: South Korean President Kim Dae-jung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Born on December 3,1925 in
Hugwangri, South Cholla province of South Korea, Kim Dae-jung, the
South Korean president, was the first son of a sharecropper family.
</P>
<P>
Before he was eight, Kim had often read reports on politics,
and when in middle school he was keen on debating and lecturing
and good at them.
</P>
<P>
He graduated from the Mokpo Commercial High School in South
Cholla province in 1943, from Koryo University in 1964 and Kynughi
University in 1970. In addition, Kim also got academic credentials
from western universities such as Cambridge and Harvard.
</P>
<P>
In 1954, Kim entered the political arena which later brought
him imprisonment because of his participation in democratic
activities. During his 45-year political career, Kim was elected
lawmaker six times and ran for the South Korean presidency four
times.
</P>
<P>
Kim established in January 1994 the Peace Foundation for Asia-
Pacific Region and took the post of Chairman of the Board of
Directors.
</P>
<P>
On July 18, 1995, Kim Dae-jung formally returned to politics by
creating the National Congress for New Politics (NCNP) and taking
the post of the party's president.
</P>
<P>
On May 19, 1997, Kim ran for the fourth time for presidency and
made it on December 18. His election made him the first opposition
party candidate to become president of South Korea since the
founding of the country in 1948.
</P>
<P>
He was sworn in as the 15th South Korean president on February
25, 1998.
</P>
<P>
On January 20, 2000, his NCNP party was incorporated with the
Millennium Democratic Party, and Kim became the new party's
president.
</P>
<P>
Kim Dae-jung, who has won numerous international honors and
awards, believes in Catholicism and likes reading, literature and
arts.
</P>
<P>
Kim married Lee Hee-ho in 1962 and has three children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NEWSMAKER: DPRK Leader Kim Jong Il </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The first-ever summit between
the two sides of the Korean peninsula is to be held here on June
13-15, during which Kim Jong Il, secretary general of the Workers'
Party of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea will meet South
Korean President Kim Dae-jong.
</P>
<P>
Kim Jong Il was born on February 16, 1942. In 1960, he studied
in the politics and economics department of Kim Il Sung University
and graduated four years later.
</P>
<P>
Kim Jong Il started working for the Central Committee of the
Workers' Party of Korea (WPK) in 1964. In 1973, he was elected
secretary of the committee and in February the next year, member
of the Political Bureau of the Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
Since October 1980, Kim Jong Il has been member of the
Presidium of Politburo and secretary of the Central Committee of
WPK and member of the Central Military Commission.
</P>
<P>
From 1982 to 1998, Kim had been elected deputy to every Supreme
People's Assembly. In May 1990, he was elected First Vice-Chairman
of the National Defense Commission. From December 1991 to April
1993, he was Supreme Commander of the Korean People's Army and
Chairman of the National Defense Commission.
</P>
<P>
On October 8, 1997, Kim Jong Il was elected General Secretary
of WPK. In September 1998, he was reelected Chairman of the
National Defense Commission.
</P>
<P>
Kim Jong Il was twice honored "Hero of the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea" in 1975 and 1982 respectively. In 1992, he was
given the title of Marshal of the DPRK. He has also received Kim
Il Sung Order for three times and many other awards and honors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
