<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Exporters Fear EU Trade Barriers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Thai exporters and officials are
worried that the European Union (EU) could ban the import of Thai
products on health grounds without giving any warning, The Bangkok
Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government has expressed its concern to the EU, which
sought the reaction of trading partners to its regulations.
</P>
<P>
The EU has become increasingly worried about food safety,
following health scares over dioxin in animal feed. Monitoring
will be carried out by the European Food Authority, which is to be
established soon.
</P>
<P>
A Thai Commerce Ministry official was quoted as saying the main
worry for Thailand was a possible sudden ban on food imports on
health grounds.
</P>
<P>
Thai exporters have hired consultants to study the implications.
A senior executive of Charoen Pokphan Group, Thailand's largest
agro-industry company, was quoted as saying the issue was of more
serious immediate concern to the food industry than the debate
over genetic modification.
</P>
<P>
The EU is the third-largest export market for Thai food,
purchasing products worth 35 billion baht (909 million U.S.
dollars) last year, behind the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government has hired European consultants to analyze
EU moves on the issue. It has also asked the EU to avoid making
assumptions without scientific support.
</P>
<P>
The EU has also been urged to reconsider its procedures for
tracing food ingredients to their point of origin and delay the
enforcement of practices related to food until they have full
international recognition. Thailand has asked the EU for help in
building laboratories and providing production technology.
</P>
<P>
Thailand disagrees with the EU attempt to link the issue of
environment, human rights and animal welfare with those of
processing and production standards and regulatory procedures,
claiming that this would create a disguised trade barrier,
inconsistent with World Trade Organization agreements.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is worried that the European Food Authority might
become a tool for artificial trade barriers and suggests that the
authority instead help improve food-testing agencies in developing
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0282 </DOCNO>
