<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Current Account Surplus Surges in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 12 (Xinhua) - Japan's current account surplus in
April rose 40.2 percent from a year earlier to 1,181.4 billion yen
(11.2 billion U.S. dollars), up for the third straight month, the
Finance Ministry said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The upsurge in the current account surplus came as a climb in
exports outweighed an increase in imports, the ministry said in a
preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
Exports grew 8.3 percent to 4,202.9 billion yen (39.8 billion
dollars) while imports went up 8.2 percent to 2,918.7 billion yen
(27.7 billion dollars), both racking up growth for six months in a
row.
</P>
<P>
The surplus in goods and services trade totaled 773.6 billion
yen (7.3 billion dollars), up 41.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The merchandise trade surplus increased 8.4 percent to 1,284.2
billion yen (12.2 billion dollars), while the services deficit
contracted to 510.6 billion yen (4.8 billion dollars) due to
scaled-back deficits in trade-related services.
</P>
<P>
The yen averaged 105.48 to the dollar in February, compared
with 119.81 a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The current account balance represents the difference between a
nation's income from foreign sources and foreign obligations
payable, excluding net capital investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
