<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Petroleum Congress Opens in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The 16th World Petroleum Congress (
WPC) opened late Sunday in Calgary, Canada, with about 3,000
delegates from over 90 countries attending the international forum
on the latest development of petroleum linked technology and
issues.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien welcomed the opening of
the first WPC event of the 21st century in his country, saying
that Canada, as one of the top 10 petroleum-producing nations in
the world, "is now at work creating new, cutting-edge technologies.
"
</P>
<P>
"We in Canada believe that climate change is real. That we must
adapt. And that the demand for low carbon or carbon free energy
will grow," he said, adding Canada is looking upon "this historic
environmental challenge as an economic opportunity."
</P>
<P>
"We are committed to making Canada the place to be for new
energy development and investment," said the prime minister in his
opening speech.
</P>
<P>
The five-day gathering, which will last till Thursday, is
devoted to issues ranging from energy prices, new technology to
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
As many as 330 technical papers will be presented to the
meeting with about 25 percent of them focusing on environmental,
social and sustainable development issues, according to Jim Gray,
chairman of the Canadian Organizing Committee for WPC.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, police have beefed up their presence in the city of
more than 820,000 in the western province of Alberta as hundreds
of protesters marched through downtown Calgary Sunday afternoon to
voice their concern about industrial development at the cost of
environment.
</P>
<P>
Since its first meeting in London in 1933, WPC meets every four
years to discuss technological, financial and scientific issues of
the petroleum industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
