<HEADLINE> Group of Rio to Examine Millennium UN Gathering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, June 12 (Xinhua)--The 14th summit of the Group of Rio
will study forthcoming UN millennium gathering and reforming of
the international financial system, said Monday Foreign Relations
Minister of Colombia, Guillermo Fernandez de Soto.
</P>
<P>
Colombia's diplomatic head emphasized, among other issues,
prohibition involving underaged in armed conflicts, disarmament
and attending to natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
Group of Rio will look for a common stance among the millennium
gathering of United Nations Organization (UNO).
</P>
<P>
The summit is slated to open on June 15 in Cartagena of
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica's President, Miguel Angel Rodriguez, will renew his
country's proposal to attend the Group of Rio in name of 40
million Central Americans.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said that President of Paraguay, Luis
Gonzalez Macchi, suspended attending the summit, because of his
country's internal problems. In his place, Foreign Relations
Minister Juan Esrteban Aguirre, will participate in the event.
</P>
<P>
At Group of Rio's summit, leaders will approve several
documents prepared by technical delegates and Foreign Ministers
on June 12,13 and 14, and at the meeting's end will sign a joint
statement.
</P>
<P>
Heads of State and Government of Group of Rio have met up every
year since 1987 to strengthen political and economic relations
between countries of Latin America and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
The group's First summit Meeting took place on November 29,
1987 in Acapulco, Mexico, with the participation of Presidents of
Argentina, Brazil, Panama, Peru, Colombia, Mexico, Venezuela and
Uruguay, members of Group of Eight.  
</P>
</TEXT>
