<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fighting Drives Namibians to Seek Asylum in Botswana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of Namibians fleeing
fighting in the border areas between the Namibian army and the
Angolan rebels have crossed into Botswana, an Botswanan official
said in the capital Gaborone on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Botswanan President spokesman Festus Mogae Petlagano Gabasiane
said 896 Namibians seeked refuge in Botswana between January and
April this year, according to the South African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
"They were fleeing as a result of fighting between the Namibian
Defence Force and UNITA (National Union for the Total Independence
of Angola)," said Gabasiane.
</P>
<P>
Some 327 Angolans fled to Botswana in the same period to escape
fighting between UNITA and the Angolan government troops, the
spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
"They are running away from the war. That emerged from
preliminary interviews," he said.
</P>
<P>
Some 50 people have been killed on Namibia's northern border
with Angola since Namibia allowed the Angolan government forces to
use Namibian soil as a launch pad for attacks on UNITA last
December.
</P>
<P>
The Namibian government accused UNITA of launching cross-border
raids on its citizens.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan and Namibian asylum-seekers are being held in the
Dukwi refugee camp north of Gaborone.
</P>
<P>
The refugees were being interviewed by representatives of the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees and the Botswanan
government to establish whether they qualify for asylum, Gabasiane
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
