<HEADLINE> Tanzanians Urged to Protect Youth From HIV/AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President Benjamin
Mkapa urged his fellow citizens on Monday to protect the young
people from falling victim to the wide spread of HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
In an opening speech for the annual Uhuru (Freedom) Torch Race
with the theme of "Year 2000 Youth against HIV/AIDS", he called on
Tanzanians to uproot the common belief that youth are HIV/AIDS
free thus making adults both male and female hunting for them.
</P>
<P>
"These are shameful habits that need to be fought by everybody
in the society and anybody with such a habit should stop it
immediately," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also encouraged his people to uphold some beneficial tribe
traditions like total banning of sexual practices before or
outside marriage.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that high unemployment had forced many youth
especially young women into commercial sex.
</P>
<P>
"In Tanzania it is estimated that in every two barmaids and
every two commercial sex workers, one is HIV/AIDS positive," he
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Mkapa appealed to parents to advise their children
to undertake HIV/AIDS test prior to marriage and to openly discuss
the subject as it is the only way of reducing the spread of the
fatal disease.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that among every 100 Tanzanians, ten are HIV
positive, mostly young people under the age of 40 years old.
</P>
</TEXT>
