<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
congratulated Monday afternoon Brice Fleutiaux, the French
freelance photographer who was freed by the Russians after living
in captivity for eight months in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone conversation with Fleutiaux, Chirac also asked
about his health situation and said he was ready to meet him as
soon as he returns to France, said French presidential spokeswoman
Catherine Colonna.
</P>
<P>
Fleutiaux was also received for half an hour by Russian
President Vladimir Putin Monday afternoon in the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Interior Ministry said that Fleutiaux, 32, was
freed Monday by Russian security forces in a military operation
without deal or ransom.
</P>
<P>
The details about the situation of his liberation remain
unknown.
</P>
<P>
He was kidnapped by Chechen rebels on October 1, 1999, soon
after he arrived at Grozny.
</P>
<P>
His fate drew great attention from the public in France after a
dramatic video tape on which he was seen wearing a black Caucasus
cap and black costume in his captivity was shown on French
television.
</P>
<P>
On the video tape, apparently taken with professional
techniques, he was seen kowtow to the audience pleading for help
to obtain his release.
</P>
<P>
Fleutiaux's parents, wife and brother all expressed relief
after the French and Russian governments announced his freedom
earlier Monday.
</P>
<P>
The photographer is due to return to Paris Tuesday. 
</P>
