<HEADLINE> Mandela Arrives in Burundi for Further Mediation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Chief mediator for Burundi's
conflict Nelson Mandela arrived in the Burundian capital of
Bujumbura on Monday to press for further progress toward ending
the seven-year civil war, South African Press Association
reported.
</P>
<P>
On arrival at the Bujumbura International Airport, the former
South African president immediately headed for a meeting with
Burundian President Pierre Buyoya.
</P>
<P>
During his three-day visit, Mandela is also expected to meet
Burundi's top military officials and visit a regroupment camp
south of Bujumbura.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Mandela last week in Johannesburg, Buyoya
agreed to close down all of the camps by July 31, where more than
300,000 Hutu civilians live.
</P>
<P>
Buyoya also agreed to integrate the Hutu rebels into Burundi's
army, which is now made up almost entirely of Tutsis who dominate
the country's government and economy.
</P>
<P>
More than 200,000 people have been killed since the civil war
between Tutsi-led government and Hutu rebels broke out in 1993.
</P>
