<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Taxes On Pay Among Lowest In EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Tax and social security deductions
in Britain are among the lowest in the European Union, according
to a study published Monday.
</P>
<P>
But average earnings in the UK lag behind those in many high-
tax European countries, putting take-home pay in the UK in the
middle of the league table, said the study by William Mercer, the
management consultants.
</P>
<P>
Average British annual take-home pay amounts to 15,819 pounds,
well behind the German average of 18,550 pounds and the French
average of 16,899 pounds.
</P>
<P>
Executives in the UK lie fourth in the EU executive pay table,
with average post-tax earnings of 42,512 pounds but UK workers are
only eighth in the wider EU table.
</P>
<P>
The range of tax burdens in the EU is as wide as ever,
according to the research. The proportion of pay withheld runs
from 18 percent in the Irish Republic to 42 percent in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Mercer said that generous state benefits are not always
accompanied by high tax and social security contributions. Spain,
Greece and Portugal are low down the EU table of contribution
scales, with employers paying much of the burden.
</P>
<P>
David Formosa, senior researcher at Mercer, said: "Despite the
pressures for tax harmonization, it's unlikely the high tax
countries will make significant reductions in the near future."
</P>
<P>
"Generous social security systems will be hard to cut back," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
