<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0395 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Family Hits Highest Level in Decade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- As a result of steady economic
growth in 1998, the average income for Canadian families reached
its highest level in 10 years, Statistics Canada reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
After adjustments for inflation, the after-tax family income
was up 3.7 percent to 49,626 Canadian dollars (about 33,656 U.S.
dollars) in 1998, as compared with the previous year.
</P>
<P>
For singles, the average increased by 2.4 percent to 21,067
Canadian dollars (about 14,288 U.S. dollars), while after-tax
income for couples with children under 18 years of age averaged 55,
074 dollars(about 37,351 U.S. dollars), 4.7 percent higher than in
1997, according to the official statistical agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
