<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda to Double Cargo Transport Via Tanzanian Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 12 (Xinhua) -- A senior Ugandan official
has said that Uganda has planned to increase cargo handled through
Tanzania's Dar es Salaam Port from the current 15,000 tons to
30,000 tons per month by December 2000.
</P>
<P>
The East African, a Nairobi-based English weekly, Monday quoted
the resident representative of the Uganda Railways Corporation in
Tanzania Godfrey Tindimwebwa as saying that the Dar port handled
an average of 4,000 to 5,000 tons of Ugandan cargoes monthly in
1996 and 1997, the amount has been increased to between 15,000 and
22,000 tons a month at present.
</P>
<P>
The official said that many Ugandan businessmen have resorted
to the Dar port because it is less congested than the traditional
port of Mombasa in Kenya though clearing goods through the Mombasa
port is cheaper.
</P>
<P>
It costs 832 U.S. dollars to clear and transport a 20-foot
container from Mombasa to Kampala, Tindimwebwa said, adding that
while it costs about 1,534 dollars to clear and ship the same
container from Dar to Kampala.
</P>
<P>
While Mombasa may be cheaper than Dar, "businessmen worry more
about timely delivery of cargo," he said, adding "what a customer
wants is safety to goods, and the shortest transit time."
</P>
<P>
He said he is hopeful that handling and transportation costs of
Ugandan cargoes via Dar port will go down after negotiations with
the Tanzania Railways Corporation and the Tanzania Harbor
Authority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
