<HEADLINE> Former University Don to Lead Center-Left Party in Ghana Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- A former university don has been
elected as the presidential candidate for the center-left
Convention People's Party (CPP) to contest the December's
elections in Ghana, the Ghana News Agency reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Professor George Hagan, former dean of the Institute of African
Studies, University of Ghana, won 58.8 percent of the vote of the
delegates of his party in a run-off on Sunday and immediately
named Alhaji Ibrahim Mahama, a lawyer who supported him in the
run-off, as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
The CPP is an off-shoot of a party with the same name that was
founded and led by Ghana's first president Kwame Nkrumah who was
ousted in a coup engineered by the Central Intelligence Agency of
the United States in 1966.
</P>
<P>
Nkrumah, a fiery socialist, died in Romania in 1972.
</P>
<P>
The party has been struggling to regain its feet in recent
times. Its off-shoot, the People's National Party, won the poll in
1979 but was ousted by President Jerry Rawlings in the 1981
elections.
</P>
<P>
The CPP is the fifth party to declare their candidates for the
December elections.
</P>
<P>
President Rawlings had announced that he would not participate
in the contest. His party, the National Democratic Congress, has
nominated Vice President John Mills as its presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the center-right New Patriotic Party (NPP) has
nominated John Kufuor, the United Ghana Movement, a break-away
group of the NPP, has elected Charles Wereko-Brobby, and the
People's National Convention, a break-way of the CPP, has named
Edward Mahama as candidates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
