<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Golan Druze Scuffle with Israeli Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Over 100 Druze residents on the
Golan Heights scuffled with Israeli police Monday morning for being
unable to enter Syria to attend Tuesday's funeral for late Syrian
President Hafez al-Assad.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of Druze people had been gathering at the Quneitra
Border Gate between Syria and the Israeli-occupied Golan Heights
since early morning, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
They were waiting for making their journey to Damascus for the
funeral of Assad, who died of heart attack Saturday at age 69.
</P>
<P>
However, among the 180 Druze who were permitted to travel for
this purpose by the Israeli Interior Ministry, only some 50 were
allowed to cross over by the Syrian side. The Syrians did not give
the reason for turning back the others.
</P>
<P>
Israeli soldiers and riot police tried to block the crowd, but
many of the Druze vented their anger and frustration at them. Some
pushing and shoving broke out between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
There was no report of casualties.
</P>
<P>
Israel captured the Golan from Syria in the 1967 Middle East war
and the return of the strategic plateau remains the major
contention point between Israeli and Syrian negotiators since they
began peace talks in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
There are nearly 17,000 Druze residents on the highland.Some 3,
000 of them have Israeli citizenship, but most are still loyal to
Syria and President Assad.
</P>
<P>
Druze villages on Golan had declared three days of mourning over
the death of Assad, and thousands of residents rallied in public
places for mourning, holding Assad's pictures embroidered with
black ribbon.
</P>
<P>
Syrian national flags also flew at half-staff, a move openly
challenging Israel's 1981 decision to annex Golan.
</P>
<P>
To facilitate Druze's travel, Israeli Interior Minister Natan
Sharansky Sunday ordered his officials to expedite the application
process for one-time permit to cross over to Syria. Those attending
the funeral are due to return Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Students, Red Cross officials and religious figures are usually
granted to enter Syria through border crossings between Syria and
the Golan Heights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
