<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are the economic news
briefs from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates supported the increase of
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC)'s crude oil by
500,000 barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that this proposed increase is consistent with an
accord reached by the world oil cartel in Vienna last March over
the output increase if prices rise above 28 U.S. dollars a barrel
for 20 consecutive days.
</P>
<P>
It was expected that OPEC will be forced to increase production
if the world oil prices maintained their current levels until the
next
meeting of OPEC.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A delegation of Saudi Arab's Economic and Industrial
Chamber will arrive in Cairo on June 20 for a three-day visit to
explore investment opportunities in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates granted two batches of
more than 7.435 billion dirhams (about 20,5 million U.S. dollars)
in loans to Jordan for projects in cultivating agricultural lands,
building dams and developing the basin of Yarmuk river.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Demand for personal computers is expected to grow
rapidly in the United Arab Emirates (UAE) as the country prepares
to make information technology its engine of growth.
</P>
<P>
Internet users are currently estimated at 160,000 in UAE, which
is among the countries where the use of internet has registered
remarkable growth. "It is bound to result in incremental sales of
PCs in the long run, especially when e-business becomes a normal
day-to-day activity," one manager said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
