<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TNC Happy with Chinese Partnership: Director </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 12 (Xinhua) -- A director from The Nature
Conservancy (TNC), an international non-governmental organization,
declared Monday that her organization is happy with its Chinese
partnership in promoting nature conservation and has made very
good successes in its project in China's Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
"The thing really remarkable is that it is really a joint
project and we are working very closely together just like in a
family," Carol M. Fox , director for Program Development Asia/
Pacific of the TNC told a press conference held here to announce
the Inaugural Meeting of TNC Asia Pacific Council scheduled for
August in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
"We have very good successes working locally with scientists
and the provincial government" on the Yunnan Great Rivers National
Parks System, she said, adding the mission of the project is to
preserve the biological and cultural diversity of northwest Yunnan
Province and promote the long-term economic well-being of its
citizens by successfully integrating conservation and economic
goals through compatible development strategies.
</P>
<P>
Fox said a Chinese delegation of six high level officials
visited the United States some time ago to look at nature parks
and check up with nature conservation and they made a beautiful
report after return.
</P>
<P>
"The biggest challenge for all of us is that it is moving so
quickly in China," she said, noting she was told during her last
trip to Yunnan that the tourist number in the LiJiang area has
gone up from 4,000 to four million in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
She said her organization is involved in a master plan for the
area which is about the size of Ireland or of the U.S. state of
West Virginia, adding "we'll get ready the vast plan ready by
September 30 this year and that will be incorporated in the 10th
Five-Year Plan of China."
</P>
<P>
According to Fox, The Nature Conservancy, with 2,200 full-time
staff and 1,000,000 membership, is an international non-profit
organization and has been the private sector leader in preserving
Earth's rare plants, animals, and ecosystems by protecting the
lands and waters they need to survive.
</P>
<P>
Its protection projects with partner organizations cover more
than 10 million acres in the U.S. and Canada, and more than 80
million acres in 26 countries in Latin America and the Caribbean,
and Micronesia, Melanesia and Asia.
</P>
<P>
The TNC Asia Pacific Council which is co-chaired by Singapore
Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew and Goldman Sachs group's Chairman
and CEO Henry M. Paulson, consists of more than forty top public
and private sector leaders from Asia, the U.S. and Europe.
</P>
<P>
At its inaugural meeting here in August, members of the TNC
Asia Pacific Council will review major conservation and economic
development issues and make recommendations for collaborative
conservation action across the region, a press release from TNC
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
