<HEADLINE> Poverty Alleviation No.1 Priority of Aid: Japanese Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Poverty alleviation takes the
highest priority of Japan's aid to Bangladesh, Japanese Ambassador
in Dhaka Shigeharu Maruyama told the United News of Bangladesh
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Outlining the Country Aid Plan for Bangladesh, the envoy said
agricultural and rural development, improvement of social areas,
basic infrastructure and disaster management are also among the
priorities of Japanese economic cooperation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Japan is examining scope for more cooperation in basic
infrastructure areas like power generation, rail and road
transport and telecommunications, he said.
</P>
<P>
Maruyama said Japan is also interested in assisting Bangladesh
to combat serious air pollution in Dhaka and enormous arsenic
problem that affects roughly 20 million people in the country.
</P>
<P>
Japan's loan aid to Bangladesh amounted to 3 billion U.S.
dollars between 1994 and 1998, while its grants figured 2.8
billion dollars during the same period.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the investment environment in the country, the
Japanese envoy regarded political unrest, image problem and
inadequate infrastructure as factors that hinder growth of foreign
investments, including those from Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
