<HEADLINE> Nigerian Government Calls to Implement New Minimum Wage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lagos, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has directed
all of its ministries and extra ministerial departments to pay the
new national minimum wage without further delay, the News Agency
of Nigeria reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Vice President Atiku Abubakar said at a meeting in the
capital Abuja Sunday that the federal ministry of finance had
directed the accountant-general of the federation to make funds
available to the federal establishments to enable them to pay the
new salaries.
</P>
<P>
The federal government was also releasing funds to states to
enable them to implement the new wages in their states, he said.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar gave his assurance that workers in the country would
receive the new minimum wages before the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government increased the minimum monthly wage to
7,500 naira (75 U. S. dollars) for public servants and to 5,000
naira (50 U. S. dollars) for workers in the public sectors in May.
</P>
<P>
However, some ministers and state governors refused to pay the
new wages on the grounds of insufficient funds.  
</P>
