<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Conducted Nuclear Tests in Paris Suburb in 1955-1960: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The French government conducted some
of its primary nuclear testing in a Paris suburb during 1955-1960,
which could possibly have left the test site contaminated by
radioactive substances, said a report by the daily Le Parisien
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Lucien Beaudouin, a 79-year-old retired engineer at the Atomic
Center of Vaujours in Seine-Saint-Denis north of Paris, said the
Center worked on the effect of nuclear explosives on metals. The
location was well known publicly as a site for testing military
planes.
</P>
<P>
The explosives were reportedly part of the first nuclear bomb
France tested in the Sahara Desert in Algeria in 1960, said
Beaudouin.
</P>
<P>
"All were tested, the iron, the lead and the uranium. But it
was ordinary uranium and we didn't work with plutonium," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that some tests were conducted underground, and some in
the air, which could have contaminated the surrounding area of the
Center with radioactive substances.
</P>
<P>
"Pieces of uranium shot like rockets in the air. The
disintegration of uranium could have produced other very dangerous
metals and the gas could also have escaped, which was much more
radioactive than uranium," he said.
</P>
<P>
The retired scientist estimated that several kilograms of
uranium could have fallen into the field in a range of from 100 to
150 meters outside the Center.
</P>
<P>
The atomic test center was closed by the French government in
1997 and its 45 hectares of land are up for sale. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
