<HEADLINE> Navigation Resumes On Lijiang River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, June 12 (Xinhua) -- More than 6,000 Chinese and
overseas tourists boarded a ship today on the famous Lijiang River
in Guilin, in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, as a
ban on navigating on the river was lifted early today.
</P>
<P>
The Lijiang River, a major scenic site in Guilin, is renowned
for its green mountains, clear water and spectacular stone
formations.
</P>
<P>
Because of continuous torrential rains, water level in Lijiang
River rose to dangerous levels yesterday. Guilin Port Navigation
Supervisory Section decided to suspend navigation on the famous
river to ensure the safety of visitors for one day.
</P>
<P>
Yesterday afternoon, the overcast weather in Guilin became
clear, causing a drop in the water level in the river.
</P>
<P>
The water level in Lijiang River fell from 137.6 meters
yesterday to 135.6 meters today.
</P>
<P>
Some 1.7 million domestic and overseas tourists visited Guilin
in the first three months of the year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
