<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Asked to Buy More from Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam wants to see Malaysia
buying more of its goods to help in its economic growth, Malaysian
Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said Monday.
</P>
<P>
This desire was expressed by Vietnamese Foreign Minister Nguyen
Dy Nien in a meeting with him in Putrajaya near here, Abdullah
told reporters after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"Vietnam is very keen on us to buy more rice from them besides
other goods. Furthermore, total trade between the two countries is
in our favor," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Vietnamese minister also expressed the hope
that the private sector of Malaysia would increase its investments
in Vietnam as Malaysia's economy has recovered from the regional
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Among the prospective areas are the manufacturing sector
related to food industries, Abdullah said, adding Hanoi also
offered Vietnamese workers to work in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said both sides also agreed that although Malaysia and
Vietnam enjoyed close bilateral relations, the ties could be
enhanced further through economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday, Nguyen Dy Nien met his Malaysian counterpart
Syed Hamid Albar here.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese foreign minister arrived here Sunday for a three-
day official visit. After Malaysia, he will visit Brunei and the
Philippines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
