<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Takes "Cooling Off" Period in Hostage Negotiations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Monday it is taking three to four days as "cooling off" period in
the negotiations with the Abu Sayyaf to study what options to take
in the wake of the new demands by the group now holding 21
hostages in Sulu.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora told reporters that the
government decided Sunday to let things "cool off" in the meantime
to give the government enough time to examine the new demands made
by the Abu Sayyaf.
</P>
<P>
"We decided we are going to take three to four days off to
review it. Then we will see what has to be done. Basically we
decided yesterday it may be a good idea to let things cool off,
for us to examine these new demands they have made," Zamora said.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the public and the international community to
remain patient as the government exhausts all possible means to
resolve the situation peacefully.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Abu Sayyaf claimed it wanted Executive Secretary
Ronaldo Zamora to replace Secretary Robert Aventajado,
presidential flagship projects committee chief, as head of the
government negotiating panel.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf slammed Aventajado for hinting at the
possibility of using military means to solve the hostage crisis if
negotiations fail.
</P>
<P>
In Jolo, Sulu, Governor Abdusakur Tan, a member of the
government negotiating panel, said they have not yet received a
formal statement from the Abu Sayyaf that they want Aventajado out
of the panel as chief negotiator.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Press Secretary and Presidential Spokesman Ricardo
Puno said that President Joseph Estrada has not instructed any
change in the membership of the government panel tasked to
negotiate for the safe release of the 21 mostly foreign hostages.
</P>
<P>
But even if there were some changes in the membership, Puno
said, the government will not change its stand on the demands the
Abu Sayyaf had made.
</P>
<P>
However, Puno said the government will remain open to the group
and stressed that it is still keeping all communication lines open.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf, which kidnapped the hostages from the Sipadan
Island resort in Malaysia on April 23, was said to have separated
its captives into two groups for fear of government military
rescue operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
