<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drugs Abuse on Rise in Kenyan Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The use of narcotic drugs in
Kenya's secondary schools and colleges has been increasing as drug
traffickers seek to expand their markets, the country's major
newspaper Daily Nation reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to a Daily Nation investigation team, drugs are cheap
and can be bought in students' dormitory.
</P>
<P>
Solid and bhang are two kinds of drugs being mostly used and
peddled on campus, the team said.
</P>
<P>
"The drugs available include cocaine, heroin and Mandrax
tablets," a consultant psychiatrist at the Jomo Kenyatta
University of Agriculture and Technology was quoted as saying on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
"I know many cases in which students have had their exams
postponed after making an appeal to psychiatrists that they can
not manage in that state," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the psychiatrist, some students were already
addicted when joining university and others began using drugs on
campus.
</P>
<P>
However, Vice Chancellor of the University of Agriculture
Ratemo Michieka denied the rampant drug abuse at the institution.
</P>
<P>
"If there are a few cases here, it should not be taken to mean
that the whole student community is involved," Michieka said.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics by the Anti-Drugs Organization of Kenya
show that over 10 percent of male high school students in Kenya's
Central Province regularly abuse drugs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
