<HEADLINE> Talks on Ending Nigeria's Fuel Price Crisis in Deadlock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government and the
Nigeria Labor Congress (NLC) Sunday night ended another round of
negotiations in deadlock in the capital Abuja to conclude the
strike on the petrol price hike, local media reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
President Olusegun Obasanjo and Vice President Atiku Abubakar
were reportedly in attendance of the negotiation.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, NLC leader Adams Oshiomhole urged the
country's highest decision-making organ, National Executive
Council (NEC), to convene for finding a way out of the current
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The government gave no new offers during the talks, he said,
adding that NLC accepted nothing above the former price of 20
naira per liter of fuel (one U. S. dollar equals to 100 naira).
</P>
<P>
NLC launched the ongoing strike shortly after the Nigerian
government announced the increase of petrol price by 50 percent to
30 naira per liter on June 1.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that several people have been killed and more
wounded in violence in the strike over the last two days. So far
hundreds of rioters have been arrested.
</P>
<P>
The government announced a five-naira-per-liter reduction for
petrol and diesel, and a 10-naira-per-liter reduction for kerosene
last Thursday, but NLC refused to call off the strike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
