<HEADLINE> Over 30,000 Tourists Booked for Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 12 (Xinhua) -- More than 30,000 tourists mainly
from the United Kingdom have made advance bookings with Kenya
Airways to spend their holidays at Kenya's coast beach hotels.
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard newspaper Monday quoted the national
carrier's commercial director Bram Stella as saying that the
tourists are expected to arrive in Kenya in the next five months.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a recent annual meeting of the Kenya Association of
Travel Agency held here, Stella disclosed that about 30,000
tourists are destined to Mombasa, an Indian Oceanic port city in
southeastern Kenya, 2,000 to Malindi and 400 to Lamu, both tourist
spots along the country's coast.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Kenyan Tourism Minister Nicholas Biwott urged
association members to adhere to professional ethics and identify
new tourist destinations in the country.
</P>
<P>
The government is formulating a policy framework paper to
enable the promotion of tourist destinations in East Africa, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Wildlife Service will this year spend 5 million U.S.
dollars, donated by the European Union, on promoting tourism and
conservation for attracting more overseas tourists to the country.
</P>
<P>
Kenya earned 21.4 billion shillings (about 3 million U.S.
dollars) from tourism in 1999, compared to 17.5 billion shillings
(about 2.5 million dollars) in the previous year, and received
969,300 foreign visitors in 1999 as against 894,300 in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
