<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Warns Against Foreign Interference in October Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has warned that no
foreign interference is allowed in the forthcoming general
elections in October so as to guarantee the people to choose their
own leaders freely and fairly, local newspapers reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
President Benjamin Mkapa told a public rally in the inland
capital Dodoma on Sunday that Tanzania appreciates the moral and
financial support from the foreign donors and observers, but that
does not give them the right to interfere in the elections
process.
</P>
<P>
He said donors and observers can communicate with all political
parties in Tanzania, but it should be done lawfully and according
to the set procedures.
</P>
<P>
There are certain election observers who have the habit of
giving instructions and orders to the people or electoral bodies
on how to execute democratic elections, said Mkapa, without
identifying the nationality of these observers.
</P>
<P>
"Let the people choose their own leaders. If you are here as
election observers, do your job, don't teach us politics." he
said.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa also warned Tanzanian political parties against seeking
foreign instructions, saying "parties that receive orders and
directives from abroad would bring back colonization."
</P>
<P>
He promised that the National Electoral Commission will be
provided with sufficient resources to enable it to conduct
elections freely and fairly, cautioning that whoever would breach
the law on the excuse of exercising democracy would be dealt with.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa was chosen by Tanzania's ruling Chama cha Mapinduzi (CCM)
party last Saturday as the sole presidential candidate to run for
his second five- year term in the October 29 general elections.
</P>
<P>
The elections will be the second multi-party elections in
Tanzania since 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
