<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0487 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Likud Watches Syrian Situation Closely: Sharon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli Likud party is
watching the Syrian situation closely and hoping the new leadership
of Syria would adopt a more flexible policy in striking a peace
deal with Israel, said Likud party leader Ariel Sharon here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The leadership of Syria is in the process of changes and we
have been watching it closely and we do hope the new leader of
Syria will not follow the hardline policy of former President Hafez
al-Assad because we know Assad very well in the past," Sharon told
a press conference organized by the Association of Foreign Press in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Sharon made these remarks when asked to comment on the passing
away of Assad and on the ongoing transition of power in Syria.
</P>
<P>
Assad died on Saturday of heart attack and his son Bashar is in
the process of becoming the new president of Syria.
</P>
<P>
Anyway, Sharon said, Israel should wait and see what happens in
Syria before formulating specific policies in solving the
territorial disputes with Syria.
</P>
<P>
But he set "terms" for striking a peace deal with Syria.
</P>
<P>
The "terms" cited by Sharon include that Israel has to stay on
the Golan Heights and must keep Mount Hermon and water resources of
the upper Jordan River to Israel because Israel can not share the
water resources with Syria.
</P>
<P>
All those terms should be the pre-conditions for Israel to
negotiate a settlement of the Golan Heights and force Syria to make
more concessions in negotiations, he said.
</P>
<P>
Sharon criticised Prime Minister Ehud Barak for making too much
promises to Syria while the two countries conducted peace talks,
saying such promises could not serve the interests of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel and Syria resumed their peace talks last December, but
halted them after two rounds in the United States, due to Israel's
refusal to hand over to Syria the entire Golan Heights which it
captured in the 1967 Middle East War.
</P>
<P>
Israel completed its troops withdrawal from South Lebanon on May
24 and several days later it also pulled out troops from some
territories on the western foothills of the Mount Hermon.
</P>
<P>
Sharon said the Likud supports private sectors to invest in
Syria, saying economic development in Syria could help it to settle
territorial dispute with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Israeli-Palestinian final-status talks, Sharon
said it is hard for the two sides to reach a framework agreement or
a final peace accord in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The fate of Jerusalem, security, right to return for Palestinian
refugees, final borders and water are very complicated issues for
the two sides to settle, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Likud will neither allow Barak to hand over the Jordan River
valley nor the Palestinian villages near Jerusalem to the
Palestinians, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Israel-Palestinian negotiating teams went to the United
States on Sunday and are expected to continue their final-status
talks there from Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the Barak's coalition crisis, Sharon said Barak is
a good politician but lack of experience.
</P>
<P>
Coalition partners of Shas, National Religious Party and Yisrael
Ba'aliya, joined the opposition on June 7 in the Knesset
(parliament) and voted in favor of a bill asking for dissolving the
Knesset and holding early elections.
</P>
<P>
All the coalition crisis, such as the Shas' demand for more
education allocations, can be solved by certain committees, but
Barak did not pay any attention to them because he only cared about
the peace process, Sharon said.
</P>
<P>
The Likud, as the main opposition party, will do everything
possible to shorten the time of the government, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
