<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0503 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estrada Calls for Unity to Eradicate Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- As the Philippines marked the 102nd
anniversary of its independence Monday, President Joseph Estrada
called on the people anew to unite behind him in the fight to
liberate the Philippines from poverty.
</P>
<P>
According to the Presidential Palace, Estrada said at the
Aguinaldo Shrine in Kawit, Cavite province, that while the
Filipino people gained political freedom in 1898, they have yet to
earn their liberation from poverty.
</P>
<P>
"One hundred and two years have passed since General Aguinaldo
declared our independence. But we are not yet truly free. We may
have ended our slavery from colonizers, but we have yet to shake
off the shackles of poverty," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president, in making his call for unity, also reiterated
his commitment not to allow any armed group to threaten the nation
's territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
Estrada led flag-raising ceremonies nationwide to mark the
102nd anniversary of the Philippines' independence.
</P>
<P>
"We will do everything to protect our territorial integrity. We
will not allow any group to challenge that," said the president at
the flag-raising ceremony in Cavite.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that "We have only one flag, one constitution,
and one government."
</P>
<P>
This, he said, can never be compromised, and it is his sworn
duty as Commander-in-Chief of the police and military, to protect
national sovereignty "even at the cost of our lives."
</P>
<P>
He said the government will continue to talk peace "but only to
build a just and lasting peace that is founded on sincerity and
mutual trust."
</P>
<P>
The government, he added, shall vigorously pursue socio-
economic development programs in Muslim areas, including the
bailiwicks of the rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
