<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka-India Talks Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Indian External Affairs Minister
Jaswant Singh Monday continued his discussions with Sri Lankan
officials on the island's ongoing ethnic conflict.
</P>
<P>
Singh met President Chandrika Kumaratunga Monday morning for a
second round of talks, officials said.
</P>
<P>
He was assisted by Joint Secretary Leela Ponnappa while the Sri
Lankan president was assisted by Foreign Minister Lakshman
Kadirgamar and other senior officials.
</P>
<P>
However, the details of the talks were not immediately known.
</P>
<P>
The state radio said on Monday the talks would focus on the
northern Jaffna peninsula, where the separatist rebels of
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) have been engaged in a
ferocious assault to recapture their former stronghold they lost
to government troops in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Singh, who arrived here Sunday afternoon for a two-day visit,
held the first round of talks with Kumaratunga over dinner Sunday
evening.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after his arrival, Singh had an unscheduled 45-
minute meeting with his Sri Lankan counterpart Kadirgamar.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the situation in Jaffna took high priority
at the talks, although no official comment is available at present
regarding the discussions held so far.
</P>
<P>
Kadirgamar hosted his Indian counterpart for lunch at his
residence on Monday. It is understood that bilateral discussions
had continued over the lunch.
</P>
<P>
India has ruled out its military involvement in the island
nation's civil war which the LTTE rebels have been fighting for a
separate homeland for minority Tamils in the island's north and
east since 1983.
</P>
<P>
However, India has been in close contact with the Sri Lankan
government and promised to broker peace and humanitarian
assistance if asked.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the Sri Lankan opposition Ranil Wickremesinghe called
on Singh at the India House to express his party's stand.
</P>
<P>
Several moderate Tamil parties are also to meet Singh
thereafter.
</P>
<P>
Singh is scheduled to go back to New Delhi Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
Security was tightened for the Indian minister's visit. On
Sunday he was flown by a Sri Lankan air force helicopter to the
India House where he is staying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
