<HEADLINE> Jordanian King Foresees Peaceful Power Transition in Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
has predicted a peaceful transition of power in Syria and pledged
his support for Syria after the passing away of President Hafez al-
Assad, one of the longest-serving presidents in the world.
</P>
<P>
According to the official Petra news agency Monday, Abdullah
said in an interview Sunday evening that he had confidence in the
Syrian people's capabilities to surmount the difficulties after the
death of Assad.
</P>
<P>
Assad, who had ruled the country for three decades, died
Saturday of heart attack at age 69.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah spoke highly of Bashar al-Assad, the second and
favorite son of Assad who looked set to take over as the new
president, and described him as a "very smart man, extremely
impressive and well-informed of issues in the region."
</P>
<P>
The Syrian parliament has amended the constitution after Assad
died to lower the minimum age of a presidential candidate from 40
to 34, in an apparent bid to pave the way for Bashar, 35, to
succeed his father.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said he believed the power transition would be smooth
in Syria as Bashar was in a strong position and enjoyed the
confidence of all important government institutions in the country.
</P>
<P>
The monarch, who had established close personal ties with Bashar
during his visit to Syria earlier this year, said he believed
Bashar stood for peace in the region and was eager to lift the war-
torn Syrian economy out of stagnation.
</P>
<P>
On the Syrian-Israeli peace talks, Abdullah said he believed
Bashar "has a desire for peace and he is ready for it, he has
already started it and I believe he will continue with peace" after
a 40-day period of mourning for Assad in Syria.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli peace talks were deadlocked in January after
Israel rejected a Syrian demand to give back in full the strategic
Golan Heights it captured in the 1967 Middle East war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
