<HEADLINE> Manila to Exhaust Peaceful Means for Hostages' Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
reiterated Monday that it will continue to exhaust all peaceful
means to secure the safe release of the 21 mostly foreign hostages
held captive by the Abu Sayyaf on Sulu island.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said the safety and welfare
of the hostages remains the government's paramount concern,
stressing that what is important is that the talks for their
release are continuing in accordance with the policies set by the
government.
</P>
<P>
"It is not important who the chief negotiator is. What is
important for us is that the negotiations are continuing in
accordance with our policies," Zamora said on radio.
</P>
<P>
Zamora's statement was made in response to the reported demand
of the Abu Sayyaf to replace Secretary Robert Aventajado, the
presidential flagship projects committee chairman, as chief
government negotiator tasked to secure release of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
According to some reports, the Abu Sayyaf group wants Zamora to
take Aventajado's place.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf slammed Aventajado for hinting at the
possibility of using military means to solve the hostage crisis if
negotiations fail.
</P>
<P>
Aventajado has been in the negotiating team since mid-May. He
had replaced Nur Misuari, governor of the Autonomous Region for
Muslim Mindanao, upon an earlier demand by the Abu Sayyaf.
</P>
<P>
Press Secretary and Presidential Spokesman Ricardo Puno said
that it is up to President Joseph Estrada to decide on this issue.
</P>
<P>
"What is important is that negotiations continue. We will
remain open, we will keep our lines of communication open," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf, which kidnapped the hostages from the Sipadan
Island resort in Malaysia on April 23, was said to have separated
its captives into two groups for fear of government military
rescue operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
