<HEADLINE> Congo Demands Rwanda, Uganda Troops out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic Republic of the
Congo (DRC) has demanded Rwandan and Ugandan troops to leave the
country and take their senseless war elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
The Times of Zambia newspaper Monday quoted DRC Foreign
Minister Abdoulaye Yerodia as saying in Lusaka at the weekend that
the two troops came to his country together but they are now
fighting each other.
</P>
<P>
He said the clashes between the two former allies in the
mineral-rich town kisangani in northeastern DRC could be over
diamonds.
</P>
<P>
"Maybe it is because they want to plunder the minerals because
Kisangani is full of diamonds," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said all international efforts should be concentrated on
ensuring that the warring troops are withdrawn and not just
separated.
</P>
<P>
"Separating them is not a solution. They should just leave our
country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Both Uganda and Rwanda backed the Rally for Congolese Democracy
(RCD) in fighting to topple the government of DRC President
Laurent Kabila beginning from August, 1998.
</P>
<P>
In May, 1999 the RCD was divided into two rival factions and
the two former allies chose to support different sides and their
forces have clashed frequently since early May this year for the
control of Kisangani, causing heavy casualties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
