<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0529 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Inter-Korean Summit, A Result of Peace Trend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The landmark inter-Korean summit
will be held here from Tuesday to Thursday, the first meeting
between leaders of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
and Republic of Korea in more than 50 years since the Korean
Peninsula was divided at the end of the World War II in 1945.
</P>
<P>
The summit, at which the two sides are expected to discuss
issues of common concerns, is generally believed as a move
reflecting both the historic trend and the popular aspiration.
</P>
<P>
After the Cold War, the surging world trend of peace and
development has brought about a strong impact on the Korean
Peninsula which has remained by and large in a state of cold war
for half a century. Faced with the new trend, the DPRK and South
Korea have been trying for years to explore ways to ease the
tension in their relations.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of the 1990s, Pyongyang and Seoul signed
several important documents, including an agreement on
reconciliation, non-aggression, and exchange and cooperation, and
the Joint Agreement on the Denuclearization of the Korean
Peninsula. In 1994, the two sides agreed to hold a summit to
alleviate the tension on the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK regarded the improvement of inter-Korea relations as a
major prerequisite for realizing peaceful reunification of the
Korean Peninsula and proposed to hold high-level political talks.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, South Korea focused its policy toward the
DPRK on reconciliation, cooperation and exchange in recent years.
Seoul has been seeking to remove distrust, promote mutual
understanding and pursue "Co-existence and Common Prosperity" with
Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the international community has been voicing
its desire to see a relaxation of the tension on the peninsula and
peace and stability there. The realization of the summit,
observers say, is exactly a reflection of the influence of the
trend of peace and stability on the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the world trend, the people of DPRK and South
Korea stepped up their efforts for more exchanges and cooperation
projects, which helped in one way or another facilitate regional
peace.
</P>
<P>
Non-governmental exchanges and economic cooperation between the
two sides have been on the rise since late 1980s. Last year, trade
between the two sides reached 330 million U.S. dollars, up by 50.2
percent over the previous year. About 600 South Korean companies
are now engaged in trading business of more than 500 kinds of
goods with the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
More than 200,000 tourists, mostly from the South, have visited
Mountain Kumgang, about 250 kilometers to the Southeast of
Pyongyang, since a historic tour project started in 1998. The
project, co-sponsored by the DPRK government and South Korea's
Huyndai Corporation, is generally seen as a typical model of non-
governmental cooperation between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Several large South Korean corporations are now believed to be
ready to expand their cooperation with the DPRK to a wider area,
as observers noted that bosses of four big South Korean
enterprises are to accompany President Jim Dae-jung on his
scheduled trip to Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
Recent years also saw increased exchanges between the North and
the South in the fields of literature, arts and sports. Artist
groups and dance troupes were swapped and football and basketball
matches held only to highlight the necessity and urgency for more
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
A South Korean parliament member once said after his trip to
Mountain Kumgang that the reunification of the Korean Peninsula
should be based on trust, while trust should start with
understanding, which comes from contacts.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming summit, observers say, is really brought about by
the common aspiration of the people of both the North and South of
the peninsula, who are of the same ethnic group after all.
</P>
<P>
However, as the whole world is closely following the inter-
Korean summit and expects a good result, experts warned that
because the deeply-rooted differences between the two sides are
not likely to be ironed out overnight, it is not realistic to
expect much achievements from a single summit.
</P>
<P>
They said it would be the best result if the summit can become
the first exploratory step, to allow the two Kims to get
acquainted, to lay down some ground rules for future summits and
to establish a modest step-by-step agenda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0530 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yellow River Waterfall Turns Green </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Residents in Jixian County of
north China's Shanxi Province have found that the Hukou Waterfall
on the Yellow River has recently turned clear, something rarely
seen once in a century.
</P>
<P>
Experts attributed the rare phenomenon, which began in mid- to
late May, partly to a long drought this year, as sharply reduced
surface flow brought much less silt into the 5,464 km long river,
China's second largest after the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
To ease the widespread drought, water from the reservoirs on
the upper reaches has been released at regular intervals to the
lower reaches.
</P>
<P>
The clear and green waterfall will become muddy and brown again
as the rain season comes, experts said.
</P>
<P>
The Hukou Waterfall, about 46 km west of Jixian county seat, is
a well-known tourist attraction in north China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0531 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Police Cracks Ring in Illegal Macaque Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Police in central China's Henan
Province have cracked a ring charged with illegally trading 2,168
macaques, a wild animal protected by the State.
</P>
<P>
The six-member ring have involved in 55 cases of macaque-
trading in 1998 and 1999 alone, according to the five suspects
arrested.
</P>
<P>
The police intercepted a mini-bus carrying 99 macaques early
this year after receiving a report. They arrested three ring
members in the bus and discovered a notebook which kept a track of
every trade of the macaque by the ring.
</P>
<P>
So far, the five suspects have been handed over to the local
procuratorate for public prosecution while the sixth suspect at
large has been put on a wanted list. 
</P>
</TEXT>
