<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Government Maintains Vital Supply Routes to Jaffna </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government said
Monday that it is maintaining vital supply routes to the embattled
northern Jaffna peninsula despite reports of supply routes being
disrupted due to Tamil Tiger rebels' fire.
</P>
<P>
"Military equipment and other necessities including food items
are being unloaded at both Kankesanturai (KKS) and Point Pedro
harbors continuously," said a government statement.
</P>
<P>
It said movement of troops and civilians in and out of Jaffna
takes place both by air and sea without any hindrance.
</P>
<P>
The government statement came as the separatist rebels of
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) were reported to have
blocked supply routes to the Jaffna peninsula by shelling the air
force base and the sea port in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Times here reported that LTTE rebels fired on the
air base at Palaly and also rendered the KKS port useless for
government troops.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels, fighting a 17-year war to carve out a separate
homeland for minority Tamils in the island's north and east, have
since April been engaged in a ferocious assault in a bid to
recapture their former stronghold of Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the government stopped flying fixed-wing
aircraft to Palaly. Only helicopters were allowed to fly to the
base, located adjacent to the government's largest military
garrison on the peninsula, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
The bombardment of the air base and the port posed a serious
problem for the government. The disruption of supply routes might
cause disastrous consequences to government troops who have vowed
to defend Jaffna. 
</P>
</TEXT>
