<HEADLINE> Africa to Introduce Continental Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- African foreign ministers have
drawn a document aimed at introducing an African parliament to
foster development and unity on the continent, Monday's Times of
Zambia newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Zambian Foreign Affairs Minister Keli
Walubita as saying that the document would soon be tabled by heads
of state at an extraordinary Organization of African Unity (OAU)
summit in the Togolese capital Lome.
</P>
<P>
The thrust of the just-ended foreign affairs ministers meeting
in Libya's capital Tripoli was to come up with modalities on how
the African parliament should operate, Walubita said in an
interview after he returned from Libya via Japan at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
"There is general consensus that Africa must emerge united and
forge ahead. We reached a compromise after considering documents
presented by Libya and Mali. The heads of state will now consider
what kind of African union to come up with," he said.
</P>
<P>
Many countries feel Africa is too weak to stand the adverse
effects of globalization, he said, noting that the African union
would ensure conflicts become a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
Parliamentarians of the African parliament would be voted for
either on geographical location, population or proportional
representation, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
