<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0572 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronology of Major Events on Korean Peninsula Since World War II </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The following is a chronology of
major events on the Korean Peninsula since the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
-- August 15, 1945: The Korean peninsula was liberated from 35-
year-long Japanese colonial rule, and was later divided into the
north part and the south part with the 38th parallel as the border
line.
</P>
<P>
--1948: The government of the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK) was established, headed by Kim Il Sung. Li Seiung-man
was elected as the first president of South Korea.
</P>
<P>
--1950: Korea War broke out. About 2.4 million soldiers and 4.4
million civilians were killed or injured during the three-year war.
</P>
<P>
--1953: Korean War ends, and a four-kilometer wide
demilitarized zone was established to separate the north and the
south.
</P>
<P>
--1983: The north-south trade kicks off as South Korea pursues
import liberalization.
</P>
<P>
--1985: The DPRK and South Korea exchanged visits of a total of
151 literary and art workers and journalists to each other's
capital.
</P>
<P>
--1988: South Korea formally implements the policy of economic
openness to the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
--1990: The DPRK and South Korea held in Seoul the first
premier-lever negotiation since 1945.
</P>
<P>
--1991: Both the DPRK and South Korea joined the United Nations.
On December 13, premiers of the DPRK and South Korea signed the
Accord on Reconciliation, Mutual Non-Aggression and Cooperation.
The two sides signed the Joint Declaration on The Denuclearization
in the Korean Peninsula on December 31.
</P>
<P>
--1992: South Korea established diplomatic relation with the
People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
--July 8, 1994: DPRK President Kim Il Sung died of heart attack.
A scheduled DPRK-South Korea summit on July 25 had to be canceled.
</P>
<P>
--1995: The South Korean government granted two companies'
direct investment to the DPRK -- the first of the kind. A cargo
line between port Najin of the DPRK and port Pusan of South Korea
was inaugurated in November as the first direct cargo line between
the two sides.
</P>
<P>
--1996: U.S. and South Korean leaders jointly proposed to hold
negotiations with the participation of the DPRK, South Korea,
China and the United States to discuss the establishment of a new
peace mechanism to replace the truce treaty signed in 1953.
</P>
<P>
--January, 1997: The DPRK, South Korea, China and the United
States held the first meeting on the Korean Peninsula issue in
Geneva.
</P>
<P>
--In 1998: South Korea's Hyundai Group's honorary president
Chung Ju-yung paid a visit to the DPRK by crossing the truce
village of Panmunjom, and reached an agreement with the DPRK on
the development of Mount Kumgang tourism resort. On August 31, the
DPRK successfully launched a satellite, sending a shock wave
through South Korea, Japan and the United States. On October 27,
Chung paid his second visit to Pyongyang and met DPRK leader Kim
Jong Il.
</P>
<P>
--June 1999: Naval ships from South Korea and the DPRK
confronted and exchanged fire in the Yellow Sea in the first large-
scale naval conflict between the two sides since the armistice.
</P>
<P>
--January 2000: South Korean President Kim Dae-jung, in his
News Year's speech, proposed consultations between related
institutions of the South and the North for the establishment of
an economic community involving both sides.
</P>
<P>
--April 10, 2000: Both South Korea and the DPRK announced that
Kim Dae-jung and DPRK National Defense Commission Chairman Kim
Jong Il will hold an inter-Korean summit in the DPRK capital of
Pyongyang on June 12-14.
</P>
<P>
--June 10, 2000: The DPRK postponed the scheduled summit by one
day for technical reasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0573 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Historians From 3 Countries Find New Crimes of Japanese Invaders in Dongning Fortress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Historians from China, Japan and
Russia have recently found new evidence in the Japanese Dongning
fortress in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province that Japanese
invaders committed "unforgivable crimes" in China during the 1930s
and early 1940s.
</P>
<P>
The Dongning fortification is located at the Sino-Russian
border, covering an area of 93-km wide at the front and 50-km in
length. Some 130,000 Japanese soldiers once stationed there.
</P>
<P>
Jin Weibai and Cheng Penghan from a memorial hall said the
underground tunnels, a Japanese command center, an electricity
generation center and ammunition warehouse were discovered in the
fortress.
</P>
<P>
Military documents were also found, said Makota Kikuchi, a
researcher from a Japanese research institute who specializes in
studying Japanese fortifications in northeast China.
</P>
<P>
The historians chose Dongning because there are still forced
labor and comfort women survivors in the area. Zhu Jinhuan, a
Chinese labor survivor, said Japanese soldiers would put those
Chinese labors who want to escape in sacks and threw them at
hungry, ferocious dogs.
</P>
<P>
Russian experts Ivan Novich and Victor Lovich said "It is
ridiculous that Japanese right-wings activists are trying to deny
that Japan invaded China during this period. All the evidence
suggests the complete opposite."
</P>
<P>
Haruichi Takenouchi, another expert from the Japanese Institute,
said, the findings in the Dongning fortification told us that the
Japanese committed untold atrocities. He promised not to stop his
efforts in exposing that until the Japanese government formally
apologizes to the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
A twenty page photo album published by the Japanese includes
pictures on Japanese attacks of Nanjing, air raids over Chongqing
and Xi'an, and also photos of their commanders.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
