<HEADLINE> Thailand, South Korea Study Ways to Boost Bilateral Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and South Korea are
studying methods to strengthen bilateral trade, a Thai official
was quoted by Monday's Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Tariff reductions were being considered," said Vithun
Tulyanond,deputy director-general of the Business Economics
Department.
</P>
<P>
A feasibility study would be completed this year, he added.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries totaled 2.63 billion U.S.
dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Thai trade with South Korea has plenty of room for growth, the
official said, adding that this would be enhanced by a free-trade
pact.
</P>
<P>
Vithun said South Korea had accepted broad-based negotiations
with Thailand, including trade in farm products, a sensitive issue
for that country.
</P>
<P>
While Thailand hopes to import industrial raw materials from
South Korea at a much lower price than from Japan, South Korea is
encouraging its private sector to compete with Japan in expanding
investment and boosting exports to Thailand and other Asian-
Pacific markets, according to the Thai official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
