<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0591 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand May Raise Foreign Companies' Registered Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 12 (Xinhua) -- At least 5,000 foreign companies
in Thailand may have to increase their registered capital in line
with ministerial regulations that await cabinet approval, The
Bangkok Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Drafted last month, the regulations require companies with more
than a 50-percent foreign stake to submit details to the Commerce
Ministry of their three-year annual investment projections and
operating costs.
</P>
<P>
The minimum capital requirement will be the greater of 25
percent of the average annual figure, or at least 2 million or 3
million baht (51,948 or 77,922 U.S. dollars), depending on the
type of business.
</P>
<P>
Sakol Harnsuthiwarin, deputy director of the Commercial
Registration Department, was quoted as saying that if companies
did not have enough capital, they would need to increase it to the
required level within six months.
</P>
<P>
The department will give about six months for each company to
finish its cost projection.
</P>
<P>
About 5,340 foreign companies already registered in Thailand
are expected to be affected by the new regulation, as well as all
newcomers.
</P>
<P>
New businesses planning to operate in Thailand for more than
three years must bring in 25 percent of their capital within the
first three months and 50 percent by the end of the first year.
They must bring in the balance within the subsequent two years.
</P>
<P>
Companies planning to operate in Thailand for less than three
years must bring in all of their capital within six months.
</P>
<P>
The new regulation will not apply to wholesale or retail
enterprises with capital exceeding 100 million baht (2.59 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
It will neither apply to construction companies providing
public utilities or transport requiring specialized tools,
machinery, technology or construction expertise as long as they
have a foreign capital of at least 500 million baht (12.98 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Peter van Haren, chairman of the Foreign Chamber of Commerce of
Thailand, was quoted as saying that, in general, any form of
minimum investment requirement imposed by countries "dissuades
smaller investors because the costs increase."
</P>
<P>
However, he said a percentage basis was fairer than a fixed
amount, noting that there had not yet been any negative reaction
from the foreign business community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
