<HEADLINE> Pakistan Offers No-First Use of Conventional Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan is ready to make a
commitment not to be the first to use even conventional arms in
the region if India agrees to do the same, the local newspaper The
News reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
This offer proves Islamabad's sincerity and conviction
regarding the use of force in the subcontinent, Pakistani Chief
Executive General Pervez Musharraf told the press Sunday in Tehran,
capital of Iran, where he is taking part in a regional economic
organization's conference.
</P>
<P>
Musharraf also said Pakistan does not plan to do any more
nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
"I have all along been saying that Kashmir is the central issue
between India and Pakistan," he said. "I have also said that there
has to be reciprocity of response on both sides."
</P>
<P>
He accused New Delhi of raising a lot of conditions for holding
a dialogue on Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
However, he added, "I maintain my position that we need to
initiate a dialogue first of all,then everything else will fall in
line." 
</P>
</TEXT>
