<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Increasingly Interested in Lottery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, June 12 (Xinhua) -- China's welfare lottery sales have
been growing rapidly over the past two years, especially in large
cities as an increasing number of Chinese people want to become
millionaires overnight.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that 11 billion yuan worth of welfare lottery
was sold across the country from October of 1998 to June last year,
650 times that of 1987 when China first introduced the lottery
system.
</P>
<P>
Lottery has grown into the second largest activity after
tourism that ordinary people would like to spend their spare time
on.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou, the capital of south China's Guangdong province
reported 2.7 billion yuan of lottery sales in 1999, while in
Tianjin and Shanghai, lottery sales both exceeded 1 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
"Lottery makes people's life colorful. More importantly, it can
raise money for welfare projects and create jobs for laid-off
workers," said Guan Xinping, a sociology professor from Nankai
University in Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
Since 1987, China has sold 30 billion yuan worth of lottery
raising some 10 billion yuan in welfare capital to improve the
lives of the disabled, the old, and orphans in China.
</P>
<P>
Related government departments are working on lottery market
guidelines and regulations. Those who win lottery prizes will be
paid in cash. 
</P>
</TEXT>
