<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0607 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anxiety Haunts Quake Victims in Bengkulu, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Many residents in the quake-hit
province of Bengkulu, Indonesia, are said to be mentally depressed
as aftershocks continue to rock there, a week after a powerful
earthquake killed about 133 persons and destroyed hundreds of
homes.
</P>
<P>
"Quite strong aftershocks have caused residents to be
traumatized," Bengkulu General Hospital's Zayadi Hussein was
quoted by national newspapers Monday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hussein said there had been increasing symptoms of clinical
depression among residents. The most evident symptom was that
people were overacting to even the most minor things.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that people rush out of buildings and into the
street at even the slightest vibration, such the rumble caused by
a passing truck.
</P>
<P>
Hussein also said the paranoia had reached a level where some
people would rush to wake up their neighbors and warn them of an
impending quake, even though the night had been calm.
</P>
<P>
"Another form of depression is that locals prefer to stay in
makeshift tents rather than their houses, even if the weather is
bad," he added.
</P>
<P>
But Bengkulu Psychiatric Hospital Director R. Budi Muljanto
said the depression had not reached a level serious enough to
require special treatment.
</P>
<P>
Seismologist Soehardjono said more than 1,400 aftershocks had
been recorded since the initial earthquake measuring 7.9 on the
Richter scale struck on the night of June 4.
</P>
<P>
The latest big aftershock hit at 06:24 a.m. local time on
Sunday (23:24 GMT Saturday) and had a magnitude 5.4 on the Richter
scale. It was centered beneath the Indian Ocean about 100
kilometers northwest of the badly damaged Bengkulu city, according
to the Meteorological and Geophysical Service.
</P>
<P>
The new tremor frightened residents. However, there were no
immediate reports of new injuries or damage.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that international aid has poured into the
province about 500 kilometers northwest of Jakarta. However, many
residents, who have sheltered beneath makeshift tents, have
criticized the government for reacting too slowly to the disaster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
