<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conflict Spreads in Solomons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Papua New Guinea's Bougainville
Revolutionary Army (BRA) got involved in the Solomon Islands'
armed conflict, the Australian Associated Press (AAP) reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Citing police in Honiara, the Solomon capital, which fell to a
Malaita Eagle force last Monday, AAP said Choiseul and Gizo
Islands were allegedly taken over Sunday by BRA guerrillas to "
protect" their allies, the Isatabu and Freedom Movement.
</P>
<P>
The report said communications with the two islands have been
shut down by the insurgents, but acting Honiara Police Commander
John Honelo heard from radio that the alleged BRA guerrillas now
control Choiseul and Gizo.
</P>
<P>
The Papua New Guinea-based BRA had fought a nine-year war of
secession with Port Moresby until a cease-fire in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Observers said the BRA was given weapons, medicines and refuge
by their Solomon kinfolk in Western Province, which also is
peopled by settlers from Malaita, according to AAP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
