<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yunnan Builds More Nature Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- With the approval of the State
Council, southwest China's Yunnan Province will build two more
nature reserves and expand two others this year.
</P>
<P>
The combined area of the two new nature reserves of the Naban
River and the Wuliang Mountain, and the nature reserves of Baima
Snow Mountain and Gaoligong Mountain to be expanded will add 432,
500 hectares to the province's State-level nature reserves.
</P>
<P>
The 26,000-hectare Naban River Nature Reserve located in the
famous Dai Autonomous Prefecture of Xishuangbanna, boasts more
than 1,700 high plants and 227 vertebrates. The Wuliang Mountain
Nature Reserve has some 400 black-crowned gibbons which are under
State protection.
</P>
<P>
The Samage Forest Zone, and the Baima Snow Mountain Nature
Reserve, are home to Yunnan golden monkeys. There are only 1,000
golden monkeys in the reserve.
</P>
<P>
The Gaoligong Mountain Nature Reserve in northwest Yunnan will
be expanded to 405,000 hectares and become the largest nature
reserve in the province. The reserve is famous for its numerous
plants and large number of rare animals.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan has abundant plants and wild animals. By the end of last
year, Yunnan had set up 112 nature reserves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000612.0621 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Becomes Kodak's Second Largest Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 12 (Xinhua) -- China has become the second
largest market for the world's leading film producer, Eastman
Kodak Co., said the company's chief executive officer Daniel A.
Carp in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Carp came to China to attend the inauguration of Kodak's two
new plants in Xiamen and Wuxi over the weekend. Together with
these two new plants, Kodak now has 5,000 sales outlets across
China.
</P>
<P>
The new plant in Xiamen, a port city on China's southeastern
coast, has been Kodak's largest investment project in 30 years,
worth one billion U.S. dollars. It is so far the U.S. film company
's largest production center.
</P>
<P>
Kodak has set up plants in China for manufacturing cameras,
film development equipment, digital photography and X-ray films
for medical use.
</P>
<P>
Carp said that Kodak sees China as both a production center and
a booming market.
</P>
<P>
China's film market, which was ranked 17th among Kodak's
markets four years ago, has been growing at an annual rate of 10
percent, said Carp.
</P>
<P>
Carp announced there will be 10,000 sales outlets in China by
2003. He said that the market for film and photography is huge in
China's western region because of its unique landscapes and
scenery.
</P>
<P>
Kodak also wants a slice of China's digital photography market,
encouraged by the soaring demand for digital film in the country.
Last year, the market grew to 80 percent, according to China's
official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Carp said that Kodak is seeking cooperation with local Internet
portals in developing its B to C (Business to Consumer) network to
enable Chinese consumers to purchase Kodak's photograph and film
via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The per-capita film consumption in China averages one roll a
year, as compared with 3.6 rolls in America. Only 15 percent of
Chinese own cameras. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
