<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda, Uganda Forces Stop Fighting in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The six-day Fighting between
Rwandan and Ugandan forces in Kisangani in the Democratic Republic
of the Congo (DRC) ceased Sunday, Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba said here.
</P>
<P>
He said the two warring countries have agreed to stop fighting
and their troops have withdrawn one kilometre away from where they
were fighting.
</P>
<P>
The military chiefs of the two warring countries reached the
agreement to stop their fighting in the DRC's northeastern city of
Kisangani, said Chiluba, who went to Uganda and Rwanda on Saturday
and held consultation talks respectively with Ugandan President
Yoweri Museveni and Rwandan President Paul Kagame on how to stop
the fighting.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said that the military chiefs are still in meeting to
iron out the differences leading to the fighting.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said Museveni confirmed him on Sunday morning the
latest situation in Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Rwandan side said that its forces have withdrawn
from Kisangani in view of the fact that the fighting and the loss
of lives are not necessary.
</P>
<P>
Its troops will withdraw unilaterally from all the positions it
has occupied, it added.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan side also urged the United Nations to send
military observers to where its troops withdraw from.
</P>
<P>
U.N. observers in Kisangani confirmed that Ugandan troops have
withdrawn from their strategic positions as well.
</P>
<P>
The fighting, which broke out Monday, left more than 100 people
killed and 700 injured in Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda and Uganda used to be allies, but now back different
rebel factions fighting in the DRC and have clashed several times
for control of Kisangani. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
